1. f4 { I'm checkmated. You win the game.

Levi Taylor (1905)

Last words after having just lost a chess game. } { I have to admit, I'm more of a 'just the recipe' kind of guy. Sure, if I have time later I may return to read about how your magic recipe was passed down through the final words of your dear Aunt Lizzy, and how it reminds you of sunshine and puppies whenever you make it. But I just want to figure out what ingredients to use in my never-ending quest to find a gluten-free recipe where my bread does not taste like an oven-made brick.

'Just the Facts, Ma'am' - Jack Webb

Yes, I know that Sgt. Joe Friday never actually said that, but it pretty well sums up much of this course. We work with what we think, sometimes thought of as perception, which may not necessarily comport with reality. This could be a reason why club players are not always able to play well a position that Stockfish evaluates to be winning or very advantageous. In this course I can either offer moves that that club player plays well (perception) , or I can offer engine moves (reality) with the expectation that the club player will be able to properly convert the continuation. My choice has been the former.

The quote also works to address those who are like me - this Preface is for the ones who just want to get to the meat of the matter, whereas the other Preface has the Aunt Lizzy stuff, and maybe even some sunshine and a puppy or two.

---

Here is a list of the things I really do want you to read:

Expectations

The Structure of the Course

Classical or Leningrad?

How Were Moves Decided?

Definitions / Guidelines

A Very Brief Strategy Guide

---

Here is a list the things that you will miss if you decide to skip the other chapter:

A Little History of the Opening

Why You Don't Really Need This Course (But Probably Do Anyway)

Why Bird's Opening is a Bad Opening, and Why That Does Not Matter

Why I Do Not Always Select the Best Moves

The Case Against Win Percentage

How I Decided Which Lines to Cover

Do You Need an Opening Course in the First Place?

An Alternative Way of Learning the Course

---

I admit that some of these are fairly long, but think of the items in this chapter as important to understanding what is going on, and the items in the subsequent chapter to be more fluff-ish, if you wish.

So let's get on with it! } *

