1. -- { “The best way to learn something is to teach it to somebody else” – Levy Rozman

Welcome to this coverage of Bird’s Opening for Club Players. I will start with the expectations for the course – not yours, mine.

Your expectations may be that you are simply interested in learning the opening, or that you want to gain three hundred ratings points, or that you feel that this will lead you to Grandmaster level - I hope not that last one, but that’s out of my control.

But allow me to first explain what I hope to accomplish with this course, and we can move on from there.

Simply put, I believe that if you are a club player (in the Definitions portion of this chapter I define a club player as one who has a rating below 2100 on Lichess) Bird’s Opening is one that will make you a better player.

I really do try to use the words that best relate what I mean, and you will notice that I did not say that the intention was to win more games. While becoming a better player and winning more games have a great deal in common, they are not exactly the same.

If one simply wants to win more games then I feel that it would be more appropriate to employ a course that focuses on tricky and trappy lines. For the lower rated player I would suggest the Englund Gambit, which while being a horrid opening at any but the lowest ratings, tends to trap the unaware into a quick loss. In the past I have shared my experience against this opening and pointed to the very first game I ever played on Lichess – [ https://lichess.org/study/YIqFODRE ].

The question becomes whether or not a win, where the opponent falls into a questionable trap, makes one a better player. I would argue a possible divergence here, as there is a top end to when opponents fall for those lines. Traps can become addictive, and when the player comes to depend upon them they do well when the trap succeeds, and poorly when it does not. I do not believe that this dependence advances one’s actual abilities in game play.

Understand, I am not against learning traps, as they are an important part of the game. I am just against focusing on them to the exclusion of better play. Indeed, we will see that the Greek Gift becomes a possibility through the natural course of some lines, but if our opponent recognizes the possibility then we just continue play and work on advancing our advantage.

Playing Bird’s Opening can make one a better player because it is a solid opening that relies on good opening strategy, solid tactics, and proper opening principles. It is one that immediately fights for the center and uses the idea of color complexes to gain dominance.

It is a dynamic opening that is anything but boring. Based upon one’s personal style, the position can be opened up or shut down, and those positions will almost certainly be very different every game.

For me, what has made me a better player with this opening is the fact that nobody prepares for it. List all courses at Chessable and enter the search word “Crush.” You will find about a zillion courses that prepare you to play against all of the popular openings, but nothing preparing you to play against Bird’s Opening.

This gives one a time advantage that is real and can be used against your opponent, and yes, can help you win games. The important thing is that it gives you time to think about your best move. As you know what you are doing and your opponent does not, you have the luxury to involve yourself in a deeper dive in the search for tactics and better placement of your pieces, as opposed to just making a move to avoid time trouble.

For me, the ability to think is especially important. As one who is at an age where the brain simply does not work as quickly as it used to, the time advantage gives me an opportunity to work on calculation and visualization, two areas where I would like to improve. The pressure to make a move is still there, but the added time allows me to make better decisions.

And is there a top end for this opening? In Why Bird's Opening is a Bad Opening, and Why That Does Not Matter [/variation/23860636] I give my spin on why this is not played much at the top levels (though Carlsen has beaten Kramnik - [ https://bit.ly/Carlsen-Kramnik ] - and So - [ https://bit.ly/Carlsen--So ] - with the opening) . But as soon as I write that it must be noted that Robert Ramirez did a speed run using Bird’s Opening and finished it by getting to 2500 ([ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vOPD038yarU&t=19s ]) , which is a stratosphere that I will never reach, so perhaps there is no top end in sight.

I have already gone on longer than I should have, so I will end by just congratulating you for reading all of this and opening your mind to possibilities that you may not have previously considered. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
