1. -- { “The only thing chess players have in common is chess.” – Lodewijk Prins

I wrote this course for myself, so that whether or not it was published, it would be useful to me in a way that made the most sense to me. I consider myself to be a run of the mill club player, who does not remember long lines of theory, and could really use help in the calculation and visualization department. If this sounds like you then the structure of this course may be right up your alley.

I will say up front that this course is designed unlike any other course on the Chessable platform. As much as I love many of the tactics courses I have worked on, none of the openings courses really worked for me. This made me decide to completely start from scratch in deciding what actually would work for me, regardless of how any other courses were put together.

Before I start I should point out that From's Gambit is the only name that I have given to any of the variations - all others are just identified by moves or numbers. There is not much theory when it comes to Bird's Opening, and while over the years some have given a few of the variations names, From's Gambit is really the only one that all sources recognize.

The number one thing I wanted to do, as I did in my Caro-Kann course, was only deal with moves that I was likely to see. Pretty much every openings book and course that you will encounter is really designed for Master level players, as the emphasis is on how to respond to the best moves. Yes, this is important, but if one is more likely to encounter a lesser move then shouldn’t the emphasis be on working with that? I have tried to identify when the opponent plays the lesser move so that one can be aware that that was a move that perhaps can be exploited.

There is something that I have read numerous times in the Chessable forum with which I agree and wanted to address in the structure of this course. It is that a number of people are trying to figure out how to work through just the first half dozen or so moves of an 18 move line in a course. They realize that there is a higher possibility that they will see those initial moves than move 16 in an actual game, so going through those first moves are important, but the course requires that one learn every move in the variation. I hear you.

This is what I came up with. I go into a little detail of how I decided which lines to cover in the How I Decided Which Lines to Cover [/variation/23890131] section. Basically, I looked only at the most likely moves one may be expected to encounter in any particular position. This is not a lifetime repertoire course, nor would it make sense to be, as it is for club players and your hopes are to move beyond that level, right? So including every variation that one might possibly see would be self-conflicting.

There are six likely responses to 1.f4 that, through the act of playing, result in 59 separate variations. We learn the first six moves of these 59 variations. That’s it (though that is not the end of the story) . If you are Master level then you really do need to learn those 15 move lines and know them well. If you are just learning to play then you do not need to learn any moves, just push pawns to the center and develop your pieces. As you are in between those two extremes take a look at your last ten games. At what point did you or your opponent exit theory? Chances are around move 6, give or take.

Just learning the first six moves gets you started and gives you confidence that you can continue. It should be known that of those 59 variations, about 30 of them are going to be stupid easy to learn, and good news for you, those all stem from 1… d5, the most common response to our opening move.

After learning those first six moves we decide which ones to continue learning. Amazing that even though we start with variations that stem from the most likely moves, by move six we are seeing that some of them end in a position that has only seen the light of day a handful or so times. There is no need to bother with a continuation that is rarely seen, so we select the 5 most likely to be seen. These 5 expand to 13 variations and we learn the next four moves. Finally, we review of the full 10 moves from those 13 variations.

Those are the most likely continuations to be seen, but it is important to expand our knowledge to include variations that are less likely to occur while playing. We return to the list where we selected the six most likely moves and grab ten more positions from that list. Through the likely moves to be seen in these positions we end up with 22 more variations, where we learn an additional four moves then review the full ten move lines.

Of the variations where we have learned all ten moves, we select the seven positions with the most games in the database and look at what continuing play with them might be through two dozen variations. This is not a chapter to be learned, but one that should just be used to practice middlegame play.

There are what I refer to as “puzzles” and a few other goodies, but that is the basic idea. Learn the first six moves that you will probably see, learn another four moves that you might possibly see, then practice with some positions you will probably not see.

Finally, the last four chapters include games - well over 200 at last count. These are example games that continue where the course came to the end of a line (when such examples exist) . Most are club level games, but there are quite a few examples from the Master level. These can be used as a guide as to what to do, and in many cases what not to do, when continuing into the middlegame.

These games can also be used as a random collection of games that will allow you to familiarize yourself with the positions. If you start a game at the beginning you may find that it is not a Bird's Opening, but began its life elsewhere and at some point transposed into a position that may become familiar. There is certainly no need to go through all of them, but grabbing two or three of them once in a while and seeing the moves can be very instructive - as I told my kids, sometimes you can learn from a bad example as well as a good one.

I have set the default time as infinite, as I feel that it is better to take the time when you need it for a better chance of getting a move correct. Also, I suggest pausing the Middlegame Play chapter - it is basically there for practice on the continuations of more popular positions. It is best that one not spend time memorizing those moves; spending that time on tactics is more productive.

The reality is that we are not Master level and there is very little established theory surrounding Bird’s Opening, so it makes little sense to memorize long lines you will never encounter, and more sense understanding the ideas behind what is going on and spend that extra time working on tactics, calculation, and visualization.

If you have read this far (I guess you did, didn't you?) then I will briefly include how I have gone about learning the course, as it corrected some of the mistakes I made with other courses. I do not spend hours a day on the Chessable site - I probably average around 30 minutes, with some days much less. This means that it is very easy for me to get swamped with review moves.

The way I have survived has been to work through the first three chapters one at a time - mastering one before going on to the next. With the two continuations chapters I added just two or three variations at a time, making sure that I had them down before adding two or three more. This keeps the review from getting overwhelming, and to the point where I dismiss it entirely.

So far this has helped me quite a bit, and hopefully it will be equally beneficial to you.

As far as I know, the approach taken in this course is unique. I created it to accommodate the way I wanted to learn, and hopefully others at my approximate level will find the approach useful. If so, then at the end of the Preface - The One You Can Skip, I mention an alternative means of learning the course. Actually, it still involves working through things, for the most part, as was intended. However, if you want to discard the means by which you are 'supposed' to learn and wish to augment your knowledge by making mistakes, then that is an additional route to take.

Not everyone learns the same way, a fact that I wish had been recognized when I was younger, but my desire is that every opportunity is afforded to you to grab hold of this besieged opening and see what it really can do. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Preface - The One You Need To Read"]
[Black "Classical or Leningrad?"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23862757"]

1. -- {[%cal Yf4e5,Yd4e5,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Be2e3,Bf1b5,Bf1e2,Bb2b3,Bc1b2,Rf2f4,Rg1f3][%csl Yd4,Ye3,Yf4]} { “Those who say they understand chess, understand nothing.” – Robert Hübner

There are basically three setups that White employs when playing Bird’s Opening. There is no need to go into depth on each one, as that can be done independently, but I did want to explain why we are going in one particular direction.

Stonewall Attack

This is a system where White places their pawns on d4, e3 and f4 to lock in domination on the e5 square. I used this setup when playing Bird’s Opening in the 1980s, a time when I could find no information about the opening (with the exception of a book in German) and was continually purchasing pamphlets of tournaments where someone played it.

I did not have much success with the Stonewall Attack because it fatally weakens the e4 square, and if Black can get a Knight into that outpost then White struggles for the remainder of the game. It left a rather bad taste in my mouth, so it is not my direction of choice.

There are variations within the course, however, that naturally fall into this setup. So if/when this happens in the course of a game then understand that Black’s strategy should be to utilize this outpost and every effort should be made to find a way to deal with it.

Leningrad

This version of Bird’s Opening is favored by Master level players. Its identifying move is g3, which creates a pawn chain and opens the g2 square to naturally fianchetto the light-squared Bishop.

This has strong similarities to the King’s Indian with the exception that the f-pawn is already moved without having to send the Knight to another square to accomplish this, and as it is reversed White has an extra tempo. When was the last time that you felt that you could not use an extra tempo or two? (A tempo is a 'turn' or single move.)

Classical

In this course we are looking at the Classical version, which was favored by the individual the opening was named after, Henry Bird [/variation/23887051]. Instead of advancing the g-pawn, it is common to advance the e-pawn and usually develop the light-squared Bishop either on b5, pinning Black’s developed Knight, or on e2 to act as protection to the developed kingside Knight. Oftentimes the dark-squared Bishop is fianchettoed to point at Black’s kingside and provide additional cover to the important e5 square.

So Why the Classical?

One would think that following the path of Masters would be the logical course of action, and that is a portion of the calculus in the determination of moves. However, club players are not always comfortable with positions that Masters prefer, and playing in a manner that one intuitively understands can lead to better play than spending an inordinate amount of time trying to figure things out.

In going through every variation in this course, the Classical version presented itself time and time again to be the preferred system where club players find their advantage – it is as simple as that. There is one situation where it makes more sense to employ the Leningrad version, and that is the direction we take – spoiler alert: the g6 variation is the best defense against Bird’s Opening, though you will very seldom encounter it until you become a higher rated player.

I happen to like the Classical version because it is easy to learn and easy to play. The pawn structure naturally points to Black's kingside, and since the g-pawn has not been moved to g3 there is more room for a Rook lift after castling to take it to the h-file via f3. For me it is a comfort thing, but you may not be me.

If you feel that the Leningrad system is better suited for you then BoyPurgatory’s The Brave Bird Opening (chessable.com/the-brave-bird-opening-a-complete-1-f4-repertoire/course/78195/) would be where you want to go as that is his concentration – your choice! } *

