1. -- { “Chess is the struggle against the error.” – Johannes Zukertort

This course uses win percentage of club players, and ease of remembering and understanding to determine the best moves. Allow me to explain each.

Win Percentage

I remember seeing a video of a guy without proper training getting into a race car, revving the engine, and when the wheels started to turn, the car immediately spun around and crashed into the barrier. He would have done much better with my old 1966 Volkswagen.

Chess positions can sometimes be like that. One can have a winning position, but not know it and completely bungle the continuation. I know, I have been there many times. As in the previous paragraph when the guy would have been better off in a car he understood, sometimes it is more important for the club player to have a position that he/she knows how to play, than one that the engine says is winning.

This is why I have relied heavily on win percentage during the selection of each move. I have used Stockfish 15 to select soft fails (I found that Chessable's system does a good job, but does tend to miss some things) , but basing move selection on win percentage is an indication of how the club players have been able to deal with the position at hand.

By the way, I should mention that in creating the soft fails manually, it is possible that I may have missed something. If you come across a move that you feel should be a soft fail then please either leave a message on that move and I will check it out (and perhaps even toss a few rubies your way) .

To be clear, this is not an infallible system (nor is any system) . I have encountered a few instances where White's move was based on a favorable win percentage only to realize that one of Black's most common response completely turned the tables on us, as the win percentage had been based on Black's other moves. I have done what I can to filter those out.

Another issue can come with transpositions. There is at least one instance where White's win percentage is in the low 40s, but when Black makes the best move it jumps to the high 50s, which seems backwards. This was because the position transposed to two other openings where that best move had been played earlier in the game, and suddenly we are now looking at literally five times as many games in the database. This is seldom an issue, but these oddities do tend to occur in a less than perfect means of selecting moves (and to be clear, no method is perfect) .

Finally, there are times when it is hard to tell whether or not the number of games makes the win percentage significant. When the percentage is drawn from thousands of games the number has some validity. However, what about when there are only 10 games? What is the cutoff point? I have done my best to insert common sense into the equation, and when there were not enough games to give me confidence, I used Stockfish 15 as a guide, though not the final arbiter. With the engine's advice, I insert remembering and understanding.

Remembering and Understanding

There is always some degree of memorization involved - there is just no way around it. For Masters, the amount required is great, for club players, the amount should be small. If a club player can memorize long complicated lines then they might be able to grab a great advantage, but just to be honest, most of us cannot.

After completing a large portion of the course and working through it myself, I realized that I had created many very similar positions that had different continuations. The result of many of these continuations was similar, so was this something to be concerned about? Any Master level player will fight for each tenth of a point evaluation because that does make a difference to them. We club players gain and lose multiple tenths without realizing it. I wanted to make the moves easy to remember so that one could use more of their time where they really should be using it, which is to study tactics.

I made every attempt to make note of when these less-than-favorable moves have been selected, and they have followed the guideline of win percentage (or Stockfish 15, if necessary) .

Understanding has also been a determining factor in move selection. We have all seen videos of Masters going over their games with an engine and being amazed at what it came up with. What appears to be a nonsensical move comes into use six moves later, but is not something anyone would have seen.

In the same way, I have shied away from moves that appear to make no sense. Yes, you may remember to play that weird move that shocks the crowd, but will you remember the continuation? And what if your opponent does not follow the line you memorized? Will you be able to continue successfully?

In Bird's Opening, as is the case with all openings, there are basic ideas that the player is trying to accomplish. The opponent may thwart those ideas, but where one of their moves may do so the way we intended, we may be able to accomplish that goal in another way. This is the key to answering the question, 'What should I do now?' The answer is probably, 'Has my opponent killed off my plan, or can I do the same thing another way?' You do not want to be in a Mad Max situation (sorry, I just had to include a link to [ https://bit.ly/ThereAintNoPlan ]) .

It is entirely possible that an engine may not know one's plan and suggest a move that would make a viable plan untenable. Sure, if the plan no longer exists then that's fine, but trying to do something when someone is telling you that there is a better way that you may not understand is not helpful.

Summary

If you do not like what I have done then you should create your own course. Please do not take that statement the wrong way - I am very serious. I have learned an immense amount while putting this course together and it has worked well for me, but I am not everyone. Feel free to grab parts of this course that work for you and create lines for those that do not work for you.

If you do this, do so with a little devil on your shoulder telling you that you are full of bunk and need to prove why each move works. That sort of challenge will force you to create something viable and suitable to your style of play. The more natural the moves are to you the better opportunity you will have to survive the opening and be in a position to capitalize on the resulting middlegame.

I go into this in more depth in Why You Don't Really Need This Course (But Probably Do Anyway)  [/variation/23896836], but that is for later.

Of course, I always welcome your comments, and if you want to contact me directly then my email address is George.Smyth@gmail.com. } *

