1. -- { “Every chess master was once a beginner.” – Irving Chernev

It is completely understandable that we may not be in sync with one another when it comes to certain terms that are used. Instead of explaining how I am using a term each time it is used, I am putting these in one place where they can be easily referenced.

If you feel that it would be helpful to add any other terms where my use might be confused with that understanding elsewhere then please let me know and I will add it to this page.

Best Move

This is a term that could have many definitions, but I define it as a move that is determined by Stockfish 15 at a depth of 30 or greater. As will become apparent throughout the course, this may not be the move that is chosen to be played, as the club player does not necessarily perform best using engine moves.

Club Player

I love the functionality offered by Lichess, and the most essential component is their database. It allows one to look at the moves that have been made by Lichess players in any position, and filter them by time control and average rating. I made the arbitrary decision to select those games where the time control was Rapid, Classical or Correspondence, and the average rating was 1600, 1800, or 2000. The '2000' actually means that at least one player in the game was rated from 2000 to 2199.

Any player that may fall into the above filter I consider to be a club player. Below the 1600 rating can also be included within that definition, but in making the course I wanted to include only the moves that the players in the higher end of the club player definition might make.

Database

Lichess has two databases. The first is the Lichess database, which I filter as noted in the club player definition, so when I refer to the “database” then I am referencing the Lichess database with that definition.

The other database is the Masters database. This includes the two and a half million games of FIDE rated players with a rating of 2200 or greater. It also includes the games of Masters that have been imported into the database. When referring to this database I note the “Masters database.”

Evaluation

The evaluation of a position is determined by Stockfish 15 at a depth of at least 30.

Master Level

Master level is either anything higher than the club level player or included within the Masters database.

Soft Fail

Chessable allows for an automatic determination of the moves that are acceptable as alternatives to the move that is recommended within the course. I used this in the creation of my Caro-Kann course, and while it did work well, I realized that it also missed quite a few moves. This is because it does not allow for a high enough depth to catch everything it should.

There are two reasons I did not use this automatic feature. One is the above-mentioned problem, but the other is that I wanted different depths for different chapters.

I wanted to be as generous as possible with soft fails, so I selected 5/10s pawn evaluation at a depth of at least 30 from Stockfish 15. The exception was that I selected 3/10s of a pawn in the 1… d5 chapter because it is the most important and commonly played first move by Black, and really is the easiest to learn.

So how did I actually go about figuring out these soft fails? They were all done manually. This means that for every position I used Stockfish 15 and waited until it got at least to a depth of 30, then manually entered each soft fail. This was extremely time-consuming, but I felt that it was important enough that the investment was worthwhile.

Win Percentage

I was inspired to base much of the move selection [/variation/22857736] on the results found in the database by Alex Crompton's article, Automatically creating a practical opening repertoire. Or, Why Your Chess Openings Suck - [ https://bit.ly/CreatePracticalOpeningRepertoire ]. The database shows the moves that have been made in response to the displayed position, the number of games where that position can be found, and the aggregate results of those games.

For instance, it shows that in response to 1.f4 the most popular response for Black is d5. At the moment I write this there have been 996,213 games where that move was played, and in those games 49% were wins for White and 46% were wins for Black (the others being draws) . Scanning the list of possible moves one can see that the best response for Black might be e5 (From's Gambit) , as Black's wining percentage moves up to 50%.

Win percentage is a major factor in the selection of the recommendations in this course, with the caveat that when there are few games in the database this may not be as relevant as seeking the engine's recommendation. Here common sense (hopefully) steps in to determine at what point the win percentage is no longer valid. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Preface - The One You Need To Read"]
[Black "A Very Brief Strategy Guide"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23910086"]

{ “Chess is the gymnasium of the mind.” – Blaise Pascal

I do not believe that there is a need to go into a deep dive as to the strategy involved in Bird’s Opening, but it may be helpful to offer a short overview that may reinforce what you will be seeing.

/img/diagrams/384930-1677356575.pngTo start, the setup that we will most likely be looking for with the first three moves are shown above. We are striking at the center with the f-pawn, and reinforcing its control of the important e5 square with the Knight, which performs double-duty by also protecting the vulnerable h4 square. We reinforce the f-pawn with e3, as we are playing the Classical Variation [/variation/23862757] – if we were learning the Leningrad Variation then we would do this with our g-pawn.

/img/diagrams/384930-1677356778.pngWill Black allow us to continue with our desired setup? We will only see while playing the game, but the above is what we are looking for. Notice the dominance of the dark squares along the a1-h8 diagonal. Not only do we have a pawn chain along d2-f4 that puts pressure on the diagonal, but the developed Knight and dark-squared Bishop are adding to that pressure.

/img/diagrams/384930-1677356630.pngWe would like to use that e5 square to place our Knight, which pokes its nose into Black’s territory. Idiomatic would be to move the Queen to e1 to give it the opportunity to move into the kingside when considering an attack. Also notice the natural possibility for a Rook lift that can aid in that attack.

/img/diagrams/384930-1677356645.pngThis actual example from a game is the most common position seen after White has played their 6th move. We will probably castle, trade off the light-squared Bishop, and bring our Knight to e5 to put pressure on Black’s c6 pawn.

Given the chance we will take the center. As will be seen, Black oftentimes just has no clue what to do and begins to form a cocoon – the Hippopotamus Defense is not unusual. In that case Nf3 can be followed by e4 and d4. If it gains us a tempo then following that with c4 is possible, though we want to protect against overextending our position.

As can be seen, a position such as the above could also have come from the Nimzo-Larsen Attack or several other possibilities, so this is an absolutely valid direction to take.

Of note is that care should be taken that moving pawns to d4 and/or e4 should not be made too soon. The e3 pawn is an important protector of the f-pawn while it exists, and if it falls prematurely then the exposed kingside could become a major liability.

So the idea of learning deep theory is just not part of this course, but that does not excuse one from making the decision to not learn the moves they are likely to see and understand how to punish opponent moves that are not the best. When it comes time to “just play Chess” we want to be in the best position possible. } 1. -- *

