1. -- { “One doesn’t have to play well, it’s enough to play better than your opponent.” – Siegbert Tarrasch

/img/diagrams/384930-1676321450.pngBird’s Opening is named for – wait for it – Henry Bird (1829 - 1908) , an English Chess player who wrote a number of Chess books, such as Chess History and Reminiscences, Chess Novelties and Their Latest Developments, and Chess : a manual for beginners. As these are in the public domain they can be found at [ https://bit.ly/HenryBirdBooks ].

Henry Bird was an interesting person, and it was said that he 'lived for chess, and would play anybody anywhere, any time, under any conditions.' Sounds like my kind of guy.

He was considered to be one of the strongest players of his time, at least by Howard Staunton, generally regarded as the world's strongest player from 1843 to 1851. Staunton invited the 21 year-old Bird to the London 1851 chess tournament, which was the first international Chess tournament ever.

Bird also participated in tournaments held in Vienna and New York City, where he lost a match to Paul Morphy (as did pretty much everyone) . In the 1876 New York tournament he was unanimously awarded the first brilliancy prize ever awarded ([ https://www.chess.com/article/view/first-brilliancy-prizes ]) .

We may think of Chess variants as being a modern idea, but in 1874 he proposed a variant that was played on an 8x10 board and included two new pieces. This inspired Capablanca to create his own variant which is the same, but has a different starting position.

Henry Bird was a rather amazing person and one whose games can be still be appreciated today.

A collection of his games playing his opening can be found at [ https://lichess.org/study/2d3WRpQX ] } *

