{ “The blunders are all there on the board, waiting to be made.” – Savielly Tartakower

I have started and stopped the study and playing of Chess numerous times throughout my life. Fifteen years ago I created a Chess.com account so that I could play some correspondence games, as I used to play actual correspondence games where moves were made via post card.

About two and a half years ago the bug struck again and I started seriously learning. However, the old bugaboo that had plagued me long ago came back – the openings books I had did not reflect the moves I was seeing.

I tried to think of means of addressing this, first considering flash cards, then thinking about putting moves into either an Excel spreadsheet or Access database. Having learned to program 35 years ago, with more than half of those doing so in a professional capability, I felt that writing a program to address the issue might be the best course of action. With the ability for engines to determine the best moves and Lichess letting me know what to expect, it seemed like the best choice.

However, I was retired and really did not want to do more programming. I had started to put the blocks needed together in my head when I came across Chessable, and their MoveTrainer was basically what I had been looking for.

And this is why you don’t really need this course. You can create your own course and base it on exactly what you want to learn. You can use the same tools available to me to determine the moves to expect and to use in response. In doing so you will actually learn more than working through someone else’s course. With every move you can imagine a little devil on your shoulder telling you that your choice is wrong and forcing you to justify each decision. By dealing with that devil your will understand what you are doing and why you are doing it, as you challenge yourself with every entry.

But … and this is a big BUT … it takes time. This section is one of the last ones I am writing for the course and I have been working on it several hours a day for the past three and a half months, and I am probably 80% of the way done.

Creating a course the size of this one can take hundreds of hours away from what might be time more productively spent elsewhere. If you are like me then this course is already designed for you, so the work has already been done. You get to sit back and go through what has worked for me.

So I seriously recommend, if you’ve got the time, that you create your own course, and I’ll give you a hint – manually create your own soft fails. You will see patterns that give you ideas on continuations after you have finished creating each line, and will see where move order either does or does not make a difference.

Most importantly, have fun – that’s really what it is all about. } 1. -- *

