[Black "Why Bird's Opening is a Bad Opening (And Why That Does Not Matter)"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23860636"]

1. -- { “One bad move nullifies forty good ones.” – Bernhard Horwitz

Quite some time back I posted messages here and on some other Chess forums asking people how they felt about Bird’s Opening, and if they thought that it was trash to please explain why they felt that way.

It was surprising to get a generally favorable response, despite its apparent bad reputation. The only person who actually railed against it said that one only needed to play the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit (I believe that they meant From’s Gambit) against the opening and they would do just fine. Through the help of OpeningTree I saw that that person had indeed played From’s Gambit against the opening, but they had also lost many more times than they won in that situation, so I did not take him too seriously.

Looking further into it I read on one website where someone wrote, “whenever my opponent plays something like the bird, the dutch or the kings gambit against me i think wow thank you for the free game”, but when I looked at their games on OpeningTree I saw that they too had very much a losing record against Bird’s Opening.

There is something going on here.

So where did this reputation come from? Of that, I have a few ideas. Looking at the Masters database, 1.f4 is the seventh most popular first move, played around 6,000 times, whereas 1.d4 and 1.e4 have about one million games for each. That definitely places it in what we will charitably refer to as the minority.

Why Bird's Opening is a Bad Opening

Bird’s Opening is not a perfect opening - no opening is or everyone would be playing it. The important thing is to identify the downsides and address them.

Looking around I found one comment that 1.f4 does not lead to developing a piece. This is true, though it does lead to developing the King’s Knight behind the f-pawn, which is the reverse of a classic King’s Indian tactic, where the Knight is moved aside so that the King’s Bishop pawn can move forward two spaces. I do not find this comment to be very persuasive.

1.f4 does open up the e1-h4 diagonal, which specifically targets the King. This is dealt with by developing the King’s Knight to f3. However, there is no questioin that a real weakness has been created that needs to be kept in mind.

From’s Gambit can be used against Bird’s Opening, which will render a weakness to that diagonal. Initially I was concerned about this variation, but the more I studied it, the more I realized that being prepared for it means that Black pretty much just loses a pawn – not being ready for it can lose the game in a handful of moves (literally) .

So we have one thing that is of no concern, one that could be a concern, and one thing that I thought would be a concern, but is not. The thing that really is a concern is that a well prepared player will find little difficulty gaining a nice position and forcing White to struggle to equalize.

Wait! Isn’t an advantage of White getting the first move that it can make it difficult for Black to equalize? Indeed, and that is where the crux of the problem lies. It is just a fact that even though I struggled every which way out of it, there are lines where White ends up a couple of tenths of a pawn down after a couple handfuls of moves.

Master level players understand how to do this, and no player at that level (or any level) wants to hand an advantage over to their opponent - especially in the opening. At the highest levels one can take a couple of tenths of a pawn evaluation and work it to an actual advantage, and that advantage can be converted to a win.

Yes, there are plenty of Master level games where White wins, but by just looking at win percentage it is far and away worse than simply playing 1.d4 or 1.e4. That is why Bird’s Opening is a bad opening – it hands the first move advantage over to Black at the Master level.

Why That Does Not Matter

If you are reading this then you are not a Master level player. The things that affect Master level play may or may not be of concern to you. That thing about handing over the advantage to Black – does it apply to club level players?

Master Level following 1.f4

Win percentage: 29% - 35%

Club Level following 1.f4

Win percentage: 50% - 45%

This is a very big deal. While at the Master level White loses by 6%, at the club level White wins by 5%. This is something that needs to be investigated.

It’s Bonus Time! Not only do you get a chance to learn how to play the opening, you get a chance to learn how to play against the opening, and this is the key to understanding what is happening here. } ( { Following } 1.f4 { the most common response on all levels is } 1...d5 { The best and most common move, on all levels, to follow is } 2.Nf3 { The most common line at the Master level is } 2...g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 { Black understands the importance of e5 and is starting the game by setting their pieces to eventually fight for that square. } ) ( { Compare that with move #2 by Black at the club level: } 1.f4 d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 { I have five books on Bird’s Opening - a monograph that came out in 1974, a German book I bought in the 80s - I do not know German and had to learn German algebraic notation, but it was the only book I could find at the time - a Chess Digest book from 1992, and two books that one can find on Amazon. None of those books even mention Nc6 as a possibility. } ) { BoyPurgatory does mention it at the very end of The Brave Bird Opening (chessable.com/the-brave-bird-opening-a-complete-1-f4-repertoire/course/78195/) in the Odds and Ends section, and after going through more than a dozen videos on the opening, I finally found mention of it in one of Igor Smirnov's videos - The Most Underrated Chess Opening Part-2 ([ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6wK5yZmQnDc ]) .

That is the reason for this course – the most common second move by a club level player with the black pieces in response to the most common move order is not dealt with in a serious manner. Yes, we want to be prepared to face the best moves our opponent has to offer, but we cannot ignore the moves we are probably going to actually see. } { @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This highlights the fact that the club player has no idea how to play against Bird’s Opening. The second most popular second move by Black is 2...c5 . The third is 2...Nf6 . Then 2...Bf5 . Then 2...e6 . Then 2...Bg4 . Then we finally get to 2...g6 , the best response to our opening, and the seventh most common move from the previous position. } { But it gets even worse. The top seven moves make up about 562,000 games - g6 represents about 19,000 of them, which is about 3% of that total. The only club players playing g6 are 1. those who play a King’s Indian setup against everything, 2. those who played a random move because they did not know what to do, and 3. those who know how to play against the opening.

My guess is that about 2% of the time (1 in every 50 games) you will encounter an opponent who is ready for your opening and will make you fight to equalize. That I cannot help, after all, I never promised you a rose garden, but the g6 move is covered so if this unlikely event occurs then you will be ready.

Conclusion

Because a situation may be common to a Master level player, that situation may not be relevant to a club player. As seen above, at the higher levels White struggles, but as you will see in this course, at the club levels Black is the one who struggles. That is why at the Master level it makes theoretical sense to consider Bird’s Opening to be sub-par, but the reality for the club player is that this is just not the case.

And I should note that is why “for the Club Player” is in the title of this course. This is a course that will be of no help whatsoever to the Master level player, but will help the club player immensely in not only winning games, but as previously mentioned, more importantly, help one to become a better player. } *

