[Black "Why I Do Not Always Select the Best Moves"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23652966"]

1. -- { “Nobody ever won a chess game by resigning.” – Savielly Tartakower

I feel the requirement to note that I have made the heretical decision to not always offer what Masters and the engine determine to be the best move. This is counterintuitive to anyone putting together a course, but I have solid reasoning to which you may or may not agree. If you allow, I will make my case.

The linchpin of the decision is that this is a course that is designed for the club level player, as opposed to the Master level player. The highest level players necessarily fight for every tenth of a pawn advantage, and are constantly seeking the elusive move that takes their opponent out of theory and into a line that is advantageous to them. It is the hope of the author that someday you will join that group, archive this course, and move on to another course that offers those things.

The club level player gives and takes tenths of a pawn advantage with regularity, and when we review our games (we all do an analysis afterwards, right?) hope to have as few blunders and mistakes as possible. This is not to say that Master level players do not have their less than proud moments, but they are done on a much lessened basis.

That is why I see dropping one or two tenths of a pawn evaluation to be inconsequential when there is a firm reason for making a 'weaker' selection. After all, we have chosen an opening where 1.f4 offers an evaluation of -0.3, so one or two tenths of a pawn are not our major concern here.

There is one position late in the course where I recommend a move that is more than a couple of tenths less, but I will have a full explanation when that time comes. By the way, I should note that engine evaluations should not always be taken too seriously, as at a depth of 30, Stockfish 15 initially feels that 1.c4 evaluates to +0.45, then drops it to +0.23 when the move is actually played. To be fair, I try to make mention of the line the engine feels to be best at the point of decision.

So why would one choose a move that the engine may not feel is the strongest in a course for club players? I'm glad you asked, and I am tasked to offer my personal spin.

The first overriding reason for not selecting the 'best' move is that while it may be the best move for the Master level player, it may not be for the club player. Alex Crompton explained the concept nicely in his Automatically creating a practical opening repertoire. Or, Why Your Chess Openings Suck ([ https://bit.ly/CreatePracticalOpeningRepertoire ]) , and it has to do with win rate.

Lichess allows one to examine the moves that other Lichess players have made in every position that is in their database. I have selected the option to include 1600, 1800 and 2000 level play (which actually means that one of the players had a rating between 1600 and 2199 at the time) with Rapid, Classical and Correspondence time controls. That is the target audience of this course - if you play at a faster time control then that is fine, I was looking for the best moves as understood when one has time to think.

For each move that has been played in a position within the database, Lichess shows the eventual outcome of the game, be it win, draw or loss. Win percentage is a major portion in the determination of recommended moves in this course, and these choices at times conflict with the engine's recommendation.

As the game goes on and there are fewer example games in the positions we encounter, the win percentage becomes less relevant. For instance, when we are looking at a position where there are 1,000 example games in the database, the win rate can be very meaningful. When the position shows 5 example games then the win rate may not help us much. This is a case where simple common sense needs to come into action, and I have done my best to apply it when necessary.

Alex allowed me to copy his explanation of the importance of win rate from his article, which is more clear than what I had originally written, so I will let him explain from the above noted article.

'Win rates tell us how easy to play the position is. If an engine evaluates the position as a draw, but Black wins 75% of the time over 100 games, who has the better position? Easy to play positions are valuable: if we forget our lines, we want positions where it’s easy for us to find the winning moves and hard for our opponents.

Win rates tell us which engine advantages are human advantages. Would you rather play a move which is winning by 600 centipawns according to the engine but has a win rate of 10% because you need to find an unintuitive plan to win, or a move which is winning by 100 centipawns but has a win rate of 90% because your opponent needs to find an unintuitive plan to hold?

Win rates tell us the value of a rare move. We want to be in book while our opponents are out of book, but this is risky: rare moves are often rare for a reason. Win rates help you figure out if a move creates more problems for your opponent than it does for you, especially when it’s not the engine’s top move. Except at the highest level, you don’t want total novelties, you want sound rare moves backed by good win rates.'

That last sentence encapsulates this course - we are not looking for novelties, we are looking for sound positions that lead toward wins. Yes, we do need to still play the game, but it is helpful to start a race a few steps ahead of your opponent.

At the risk of making it sound like win percentage is a panacea of sorts that allows one to definitively find the best move, I have added The Case Against Win Percentage to the chapter to let you know that I understand the limitations.

Another overriding reason for sometimes not selecting engine moves is that win percentage can keep us away from engine moves that are just crazy. It is understandable that there is attraction to finding a move that on the outset makes no sense, then appears in the review as an amazing move. How many of us have dreamed of an en passant checkmate? But how practical is that in terms of learning? How much of our time should be spent working on rare and almost certainly never to be seen lines when that time could be better spent invested in tactics training? We all need to make these decisions for ourselves, but my feeling is that when it comes to openings it is best to concentrate on good winning moves, following the path of those who have come before us.

Please do not think that I am disparaging the essential use of engines - without them neither this nor my course on the Caro-Kann would exist. My sole intention here is to argue against the engine being the sole arbiter of moves to be learned at the club level. If the engine takes you down a rare path that is not completely understood, then if there are any holes in that understanding and the opponent plays an unexpected move then you could be a stranger in a strange land.

Win percentage tells us that players of our strength have successfully navigated those known waters, and if we walk in their footsteps then that will give us a better chance to be as successful as they have been. As previously mentioned, the hopes here are for you to get to the level where these novelties and engine lines do become relevant because you are no longer a club player. I wish you the best on that journey. } *

