[Black "The Case Against Win Percentage"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/30604361"]

1. -- { I decided to add the below explanation to ensure that nobody got the idea that I thought that looking at the win percentage was the end-all in finding the best move in a position. I have sung its praises, but to be sure, I am well aware of its shortcomings.

The main issue is that the game's result might not relate to the current position. Perhaps this makes invalid everything about win percentage in the first place.

For instance, in Timothy Taylor's book Bird's Opening he is playing against Ivanov in 2004 (game 14) . At one point, he falls to a -2.4 evaluation but recovers to +0.9. He then blunders and falls to a -1.7 disadvantage, whereafter his opponent blunders, and he wins the game.

When I analyze my games they are very much like this, although they typically have more twists and turns, and those twists and turns are more severe. I oftentimes make a mistake or a blunder, followed by a similar error by my opponent. Up and down we go, like children on a see-saw, the evaluation curve getting dizzy moving up and down so frequently.

The point here is that in many instances, those inaccuracies, mistakes, and blunders cancel out the better moves played in the game. I have regularly given and taken a handful of pawn evaluations during play, which probably invalidate any advantage one of us may have had.

At one point in the course, I looked at a position with only four games in the database, all won by Black. Looking at those games I saw that in two White had a winning position but blundered away the opportunity. In a 'fair' world the win percentage for that position would have been 50-50%, not the 0-100% I saw.

So there is a valid argument that the win percentage associated with a move might not be valid.

This is the other side of the enthusiastic argument that win rate has great meaning. We need to accept that reliance on win rate is as flawed as other means of move selection, which includes looking at what the engine has to say.

In going through all of the soft fails for each move in the course, I used the engine to determine what would be allowed. In doing so, I got close and personal with the engine finding brilliant moves, and the engine finding moves that, if they were relayed to me in a game, I would discard as nonsense, because to a mortal like myself would make no sense.

That said, win percentage can lead one to a position that is easier to play for an individual who is at a particular level. Some positions that pose no problem for an engine may be a source of bewilderment to the club player.

With a large number of games at one's disposal, we must assume that in the long run, things will even themselves out. In the four games I mentioned above, I am certain that there are also examples of four games won by White, but Black blundered away the winning advantage. With a large number of games, we can make the reasonable assumption that these sorts of things will even themselves out.

This is a long-winded way of assuring you that I realize the weaknesses with looking at win percentage, just as I realize the weaknesses inherent with relying on engine evaluations that we club level humans (and the occasional Master level player) find confounding.

Using both win percentage and engine evaluation and mixing in some common sense and the basic tenets of the course, hopefully, I have found an appealing mixture that makes sense when making move selection. } *

