[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23890131"]

1. -- { “If your opponent offers you a draw, try to work out why he thinks he’s worse off.” – Nigel Short

There is no exact formula for deciding which variations need to be examined within the course, but I did follow some guidelines.

The important thing is that the course is in no way under the expectation that every variation needs to be covered. It is the hope that the student will some day advance from club player to a higher level, and if/when that happens then there will be other courses one can work through that will be more appropriate for that level. By definition we are confined to looking at moves that may be made by others at our level.

Certainly, all variations at the club level cannot be examined. Even a lifetime repertoire needs to limit the near infinite possibilities one might encounter. So there needs to be a balance between making sure that one covers the important variations and dismissing those that one is less likely to see. } ( { I will use the initial moves } 1.f4 d5 2.Nf3 { as an example of the process I went through when deciding what to include and what not to include. } ) { In the resulting position I knew that the best move and the one that Masters play is 2... g6. Pretty much any resource that one encounters includes this move, and it is the only move where Black has a better win percentage than White.

Being only the second move of the game, I knew that this would be an exception to the guideline I would be using for future decisions. This is the seventh most likely move from the previous position, so I included it and all six of the more likely moves in the course. } { 2.Nf3 Nc6 is the most commonly played second move, so will continue the example after we play 3.e3 } { The guideline that I wanted to use was to include the most commonly played move, and any others that had been played at least half as often. 3... Bg4 has the most games in the database from the previous move with 44,504, and the second most is 3... Nf6 with 28,107. As that is more than half of the top move I included it in the course. 3... Bf5 has 15,148 games, which is well less than half of the 44,504, but since we are looking at what might be considered to be the “club player main line” (is that a thing?) , I decided that it should be included.

Continuing from 3... Bg4 we play 4.Bb5. @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp1pppp/2n5/1B1p4/5Pb1/4PN2/PPPP2PP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ The top move for Black is a6 with 3,353 games, followed by e6 (2,989), Qd6 (2,358) and Nf6 (2,120). As all of these are greater than 50% of a6’s 3,353 games they are included, but Qd7 with 1,338 games is not, because it is less than 50% of the target number.

That is the basic idea behind deciding what to include and what not to include. In my Caro-Kann course I used the same basic guideline and occasionally get an email from someone who wants me to include a line that they encountered. It may make sense to include the line in a clickable, but I really want to keep the course relatively short and not overwhelming for the average player to digest. } *

