[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/24485456"]

1. -- { Welcome to life. It’s a big boat with a lot of holes, but we’re all in it together - Rick Sanchez

After spending (I am guessing) around 400 hours writing this course (someone smarter and more talented could have done it much quicker) I finally got around to questioning whether or not it was worthwhile. The answer that I came up with is that it was ... probably. Bottom line is that I learned a boatload while creating this thing, but a fair amount of that knowledge could have come elsewhere. Perhaps I can offer some of that here so that you have a bit of an advantage.

I was asked about a particular position in the course (this one: @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/4bppp/p1p1pn2/2pp4/5Pb1/1P1PPN2/PBPN2PP/R3QRK1 b - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@) and after answering the question I decided to dig a bit deeper. What I found 'should' not be surprising.

There were ten games on Lichess in the database in this position and Lichess had links to eight of the games, so I decided to do a computer analysis on each them.

Here's what I found (I only included seven of the games - one game looked suspicious to me, then I saw that the account had been closed due to violating the Lichess Terms of Service) :

1-0 Even evaluation until White blundered on move 14, giving Black a winning position until they blundered on move 49 and got checkmated one move later.

0-1 Even evaluation until White blundered on move 16, Black blundered to give up the advantage, White blundered again on move 23 and Black won.

0-1 Even evaluation until White blundered on move 23, Black blundered away the advantage on move 25, and White blundered away their advantage on move 26, eventually losing the game.

1-0 Even evaluation until White blundered on move 21, then Black blundered on the next move losing the game shortly thereafter.

0-1 Even evaluation until White played an inaccuracy on move 21, leading to Black winning the game .

1-0 Even evaluation until White made a mistake on move 15, Black blundered their advantage on the next move, White blundered on the next move, Black blundered on the next move, and White held the advantage until move 29 where Black blundered again and gave away the game.

1-0 Even evaluation until Black blundered on move 15, White slowly gave away the advantage until Black blundered on move 19, giving away the game.

8 games, 32 blunders. One might think that I was looking at three digit rated players, but that is not the case - the range of the players was 1842-2189 with an average of 2010. This should give hope to all of us who happen to fit into that club player category.

There is something positive to be said about an opening course getting one through the first ten moves. Beyond that, however, we are all prone to THE BIG MISTAKE. You know the joke about not having to outrun the bear, just be faster than the guy next to you - we just need to make sure that our mistakes are not as egregious as our opponent's.

Openings are a means of getting us safely to the point where we can seek to capitalize on our opponent's mistakes. If we are able to traverse the first dozen or so moves without disaster, then figuring out how to not play as poorly as the person on the other side of the board is the key to our success, or lack thereof.

There are more openings courses on Chessable than all others combined, which is the case because we place that much importance on them. In six of the seven above games, either side could have won following their opponent's misstep. In my mind, this diminishes the role of the opening and gives more importance to slowing down, observing the position and building a strategy, seeking tactics on both sides, and making sure that one does not blunder. Yes, easier said than done, but that should give us a direction as to where we should be spending our study time.

Amusingly, before writing this sentence I literally just played a game where my opponent blundered on move 8. I just made sure that they had no chances and handily won the game. The idea is the same, however, whether the error comes on move 8 or 28 - blunders tend to rule our play, not opening moves that may gain us a couple of tenths of a pawn advantage.

Use an opening course to get you through the first couple of handfuls of moves then spend time concentrating on strategy and tactics. And just my opinion, but if you are looking for a free course to do that then I can highly recommend entering 'on the Attack' into Chessable's course search and grab one of more or AlanB's courses - they go from fall-down simple to really (for me) hard.

Enjoy! } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Preface - The One You Can Skip"]
[Black "An Alternative Way of Learning the Course"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/30503082"]

1. -- { Quite obviously, the purpose of working through a course is to learn. There are things like XP that may give some encouragement to continue working, but that is also the sort of thing that can work negatively. Working slowly does not allow for a rapid increase in this number, and that is what I suggest as an alternative.

One of my failings in courses of this sort is that I tend to memorize lines and then get tripped up during play when the line does not go exactly as written. Yes, that is a personal problem, but one that I have a feeling may be shared by others. A way around this is to intentionally make mistakes while working through the course.

Let me explain.

During the creation of this course, every move was looked at by Stockfish 15 and soft fails were manually added. Chessable does have an automatic means to create soft fails, but my feeling is that the engine that creates their soft fails does not go deep enough, thus missing a number of things. In doing so manually, I may include more soft fails than would otherwise be the case. (By the way, due to my choice of entering soft fails manually, it is absolutely possible that I may have made some errors - if you feel that I left out a soft fail then please let me know.)

This decision works well for a course designed for club players. As such, we give and take tenths of a pawn advantage regularly, so the course can be more forgiving when it comes to soft fails (I look at 5/10 of a pawn instead of the default 3/10 of a pawn) . A club player can err with greater frequency and still consider the error a success.

This is a roundabout way of saying that one way to learn is to intentionally make mistakes. When I find myself mindlessly making moves because I have previously memorized them, I occasionally force myself to slow down by looking at the position and trying to figure out what other possible soft fails might exist.

By wondering what other acceptable moves may be in a position, making those moves, and seeing that they were not chosen for the course but are reasonable and could have been successfully played, I can understand the position better.

I highly recommend that anyone creating their own course build the soft fails manually. Throughout doing this and seeing what the engine thinks of its top 15 moves, I tend to see some moves recommended over and over throughout the line. I get curious about those unchosen moves and go back to look at them to see if they are reasonable and understandable. Sometimes they make more sense than the move I had originally decided upon.

It tends to be a valuable learning experience and can be used by the student when learning a position. You may know that Nf6 is the correct move, but are there other moves that could work almost as well? If you take the time to try one of those moves, then you get no XP from that, just a soft fail - or the knowledge that your guess would be a mistake. This also slows you down so that you do not work through the course as quickly. That is a good thing. If you find that your guess is not acceptable then your accuracy percentage goes down. That is also a good thing. If you have gained knowledge by doing this than that is what is called learning.

By making intentional mistakes, you can see what works and what does not. Certainly, the move selected by the author of the course is not the only good move in a position. It is the opinion of the author and could be subject to the author's biases. Yes, you may have a better idea that works better for you. By trying to discover these soft fails, you may find that the position opens up to your understanding more clearly.

I have tinkered with but rejected the idea of including how many soft fails are available in each position. I look at the top 15 moves, and some positions have 14 soft fails, believe it or not. It would be silly to try to find all 14 moves, if only because sometimes the engine does crazy things like undeveloping a Knight that was just developed. Seriously, nobody cares.

By rejecting the accumulation of XP and not worrying about the accuracy percentage displayed at the end of each line, one can use the course as a source of exploration. Each position in the course can be used as an actual study.

Yes, the first six moves are very important. However, after that time, things get a bit messier. In my opinion, the selection of the actual move becomes a bit less important than understanding what the position has to offer. You will certainly encounter the first few moves on a regular basis, and will probably see the next several occasionally. But after that, all bets are off. At the Master level, that is not the case, but at the club level, understanding what can be done in a position, what the strengths and weaknesses are for both you and your opponent's positions, and how they can be attacked, exploited, and defended, is considerably more instructive than mindlessly knowing where to place a piece.

So consider trying to find the soft fails every once in a while in a position. It goes against the idea of working through the course quickly and obtaining points, and it works against the intuitive nature we all have of being able to mindlessly do something successfully, but it can be fruitful in actually understanding what is going on and what possibilities exist. The real learning comes when you can take something that is given and extrapolate it into something that works for your benefit.

Consider this course for learning, and intentionally making mistakes as part of that learning. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "1... d5"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21532116"]
[ECO "A02"]

1. f4 d5 {[%cal Be2e3,Bg1f3,Gb8c6,Bf1b5,Bb2b3,Bc1b2,Yb2g7,Be1g1][%csl Ye5,Yd4]} { d5 is the most popular response to Bird's Opening, played by club players more than three and a half times more than e6. For that reason there are more variations in this chapter than the other two first moves chapters combined. I do apologize (somewhat) that it will also be the most boring of the chapters in this course because learning the first six moves are so easy that going through the variations will be repetitive and simplistic. Then again, that may not be such a bad thing if we are to end up with a strong start to the game.

When d5 is played as a response to our initial f4 there is a standard setup that will be employed, with one exception that will be mentioned in a moment. That is not to say that these moves will happen regardless what our opponent does, but they will be made as long as our opponent allows them to happen.

Bird's Opening can appear as a Reversed Classical Dutch Defense a tempo up, but it will be our intention to fianchetto the dark-squared Bishop, and if there is a Knight to pin on c3 then that will be the job of the light-squared Bishop to pin it. The intention is to dominate the dark squares with the Queen's Bishop, King's Knight, and e- and f-pawns.

The moves shown do not fit neatly into the standard Bird's Opening primarily because of Black's second move, which in Master play is g6. Although this move will be covered, club players have six other moves they prefer, and after g6 their moves are pretty much 'I have no idea what to do here' moves.

g3 is the best second move, according to Masters, and Stockfish 15 (at a depth of 42) . All commonly referenced standard variations involve this decision for Black. That being the case, there is no mention of the club player's most common move, Nc6, in Lakdawala's excellent 'Bird's opening move by move,' nor Taylor's well-written 'Bird's Opening, detailed coverage of an underrated and dynamic choice for White,' nor Soltis' 'Winning With f4 ,' or even my ancient copy of Schwarz's 'Handbuch der Schach-Eroffnungen Band 13 1.f2- f4 ,' a book in German that was the only one I could find on the opening 45 years ago.

Stockfish prefers openings that directly attack the center, so Bird's Opening is not a favorite of the engine. It is, however, important to note that the engine lists Nc6 as the 13th best move, nearly half a pawn evaluation less than g6, so on move 2 your opponent will probably play what Stockfish sees as an inaccuracy. The question is whether or not you will be able to take advantage of that.

Hopefully, this course will assist in that task.

Just a note here: This chapter has fewer soft fails than are seen in other chapters. It is imperative that we cement the placement of pieces into our minds. As you will see the same moves over and over in this chapter to the point where you will be playing them in your dreams, let's try get these as exact as possible.

Also, throughout this and the next two chapters, as well as the two "Continuations" chapters, you will see some variation names followed with '(P)'. The explanation for this will be given in the Introduction to Review #1. } 
*

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "1... d5"]
[Black "2... Nc6 3... Bg4 with 4... a6 (P)"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21430258"]
[ECO "A03"]

1. f4 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Be5]} { We will see throughout the course that control of the e5 square is an important elements in White's strategy. The first move gains control of the square in a way that is not easy to dispute. From's Gambit does challenge this control and will be dealt with at the appropriate time. } d5 {[%csl Ge4,Gc4]} { In the 1... d5 variation Black temporarily cedes control of the e5 square and seeks to control the light squares. } 
2. Nf3 {[%csl Be5,Bd4,Bh4]} { This is additional control over the dark squares, as well as protection of the vulnerable h4 square. } ( { This will be our second move every single time, with the exception of From's Gambit. In the past it was not uncommon to see } 2.b3 { played here, the idea being that it ensures that White has an opportunity to fianchetto their queenside Bishop. Without this move it is possible that Black can fianchetto their kingside Bishop and stunt our idea, which is actually the best plan, but seldom played at the club level. There are ways of dealing with that possibility, so the b3 move has fallen out of favor over the years. } ) Nc6 {[%cal Gg7g6]} ( { There is a wide divergence here. Masters usually play } 2...g6 { and almost never play Nc6 - club players usually play Nc6 and almost never play g6, as there are six other choices they see as better. g6 will be covered at the end of the chapter.

Just a note here: this is a move that is very rarely covered, as most openings books and courses focus on moves by Master level players. BoyPurgatory does make note of it at the end of his The Brave Bird Opening course (chessable.com/the-brave-bird-opening-a-complete-1-f4-repertoire/course/78195/) in his Odds and Ends chapter, but we take the move very seriously here because it is the most common one you will see at the club level. } ) 
3. e3 {[%cal Bf1b5][%csl Bd4]} ( { Here we have come to another huge fork in the road. In Master level play the two most common moves from the previous position are } 3.e3 { and (more popular) } ) ( 3.g3 { .

The latter is what is referred to as the Reversed Leningrad Dutch, or (as I prefer) the Leningrad Bird. These moves lead to entirely different games. At the club level the win rate (at this point) is exactly the same, so it really comes down to what the player chooses for their repertoire.

For me personally, the ability to open a diagonal for the Bishop offers more flexibility - we can use the Bishop to either pin a Knight on c6 or break a pin if Black plays Bg4. Neither move is inherently better than the other (Masters may disagree, but I am speaking to my fellow club players and am referencing our play), so this is simply a point of personal preference.

Actually, another point, if I may. Most books and courses focus on the Leningrad Bird, so players actually preparing to play against Bird's Opening will be less familiar with the route we are taking. } ) Bg4 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gc8f5,Yg4d1][%csl Gc8]} ( { The standard relative pin of the f3-Knight. Other possibilities are } 3...Nf6 { and } ) ( 3...Bf5 { , which will be covered later in the course. } ) 
4. Bb5 {[%cal Yb5e8,Bh2h3]} ( { There is no need to think about removing the Bishop at this time with } 4.h3 { There are a few cases in the course where h3 is played, but never this early, and always with a kingside attack at least in mind. After castling and moving the Queen to e1 the pin becomes inert.

An absolute pin on the c6 Knight will be a regular theme - prepare to see it time and time again. This move does not always happen, but is made more often than not, and when it happens, is done so early on. } ) a6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd8d6,Gg8f6]} ( { This is a common move and completely unnecessary for Black. Better is } 4...e6 { , which is almost as commonly played and will be covered next. } ) ( 4...Qd6 { and } ) ( 4...Nf6 { are also possibilities, the former will be covered, the latter transposes to another line.

No Masters games in this position. } ) 
5. Bxc6+ {[%csl Ga6]} { When a6 is played we will take the Knight each time. As a matter of fact, we will almost always wait for Black to play a6 before making the trade, as we would rather have Black use a tempo to prompt this. There are a few cases where it is to our tactical advantage to make the trade without being forced, and those instances will be explained when the time comes. } bxc6 
6. O-O {[%cal Bb2b3,Bc1b2]} ( { This is a good start to the standard setup we are shooting for. Fianchettoing the Bishop will be our next task, then it will be time to decide how to proceed from there. It would be perfectly reasonable to fianchetto the Bishop before castling, and this is just a matter of taste. } 6.b3 { has often been the move in the past - my particular style has been to get castled quickly but others' style may be different. Both work equally well. Win rate in this position: 58% - 36%.

This is the twelfth most popular position following White's 6th move, so it will be continued in The Somewhat Likely Continuations chapter as there is more than a 2% chance that you will get this far before veering into unknown territory. } ) *

