Just a note here: this is a move that is very rarely covered, as most openings books and courses focus on moves by Master level players. BoyPurgatory does make note of it at the end of his The Brave Bird Opening course (chessable.com/the-brave-bird-opening-a-complete-1-f4-repertoire/course/78195/) in his Odds and Ends chapter, but we take the move very seriously here because it is the most common one you will see at the club level. } ) 
3. e3 {[%cal Bf1b5][%csl Bd4,Bf4]} ( { Here we have come to another huge fork in the road. In Master level play the two most common moves from the previous position are } 3.e3 { and (more popular) } ) ( 3.g3 { .

The latter is what is referred to as the Reversed Leningrad Dutch, or (as I prefer) the Leningrad Bird. These moves lead to entirely different games. At the club level the win rate (at this point) is exactly the same, so it really comes down to what the player chooses for their repertoire.

For me personally, the ability to open a diagonal for the Bishop offers more flexibility - we can use the Bishop to either pin a Knight on c6 or break a pin if Black plays Bg4. Neither move is inherently better than the other (Masters may disagree, but I am speaking to my fellow club players and am referencing our play), so this is simply a point of personal preference.

Actually, another point, if I may. Most books and courses focus on the Leningrad Bird, so players actually preparing to play against Bird's Opening will be less familiar with the route we are taking. } ) Bf5 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gg8f6][%csl Gc8]} ( { Bf5 is the third most commonly played move from the previous position, and weaker than the other two, } 3...Bg4 { and } ) ( 3...Nf6 { . } ) 
4. Bb5 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Yb5e8]} { The pin we will see as a regular participant. } e6 
5. O-O {[%csl Bf3]} { It is important to castle here, as we would like to move the f3-Knight. } Bd6 
6. d3 {[%cal Bb5c6,Bf3d4][%csl Bf5]} { We want Black's f5-Bishop to bite on granite. } ( { This is an even position and Stockfish 15 feels that both d3 and } 6.Bxc6+ { are the best moves. The latter is completely fine, it is just that there is no compelling reason for us to spend the tempo to take the knight at the moment. } ) ( 6.Nd4 { is an interesting alternative following the idea of 'PP on the PP' (Put Pressure on the Pinned Piece). It has a nice win percentage, though the number of games do not support confidence in that statistic. } ) { Stockfish 15 evaluation: +0.4

