[ECO "A03"]

1. f4 {[%csl Be5]} { We will see throughout the course that control of the e5 square is an important elements in White's strategy. The first move gains control of the square in a way that is not easy to dispute. From's Gambit does challenge this control and will be dealt with at the appropriate time. } d5 {[%csl Ge4,Gc4]} { In the 1... d5 variation Black temporarily cedes control of the e5 square and seeks to control the light squares. } 
2. Nf3 {[%csl Be5,Bd4,Bh4]} { This is additional control over the dark squares, as well as protection of the vulnerable h4 square. } ( { This will be our second move every single time, with the exception of From's Gambit. In the past it was not uncommon to see } 2.b3 { played here, the idea being that it ensures that White has an opportunity to fianchetto their queenside Bishop. Without this move it is possible that Black can fianchetto their kingside Bishop and stunt our idea, which is actually the best plan, but seldom played at the club level. There are ways of dealing with that possibility, so the b3 move has fallen out of favor over the years. } ) g6 { This is the best response against our setup, but is seldom played, probably because no club player prepares to play against Bird's Opening. It could be argued that this is a refutation against the opening, as at the Master level the win rate is 23% - 38%. Indeed, at the club level the win rate is only 39% - 55%. However, these are averages, so we should not lose hope, as there is one response to this move that offers White a slightly advantageous win rate. } 
3. c4! {[%mdl 32768]} { I decided to put an exclamation mark on this move because I am not sure that it would be found over the board. At the Master level it would just be "another move" - and looking at the win rate for White, possibly not one of the more promising ones. More on that in a moment. For the club player the move has a win rate of 48%-47% - the only move with a significant number of games played that keeps White positive in this regard.

When choosing a seldom played move simply because of the win rate, one needs to make sure that it is not a trash move that has had success only because of a dodgy trap, and at first blush it appears that this may be the case.

An initial look at the Masters database shows that c4 gives White the absolute worst win rate amongst the moves played. On second glance, however, the move also offers White the lowest loss rate among its peer moves.

This move has a 62% draw rate, so c4! is not a trash move, but a legitimate attempt to play against the strongest option Black has at their disposal. } c6 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gd5d4,Gf8g7]} { Here we are on only move 3 and the number of games in the Lichess database for each of the four responses to be covered is in the tens. c6 is the move Masters, as well as club players, choose, and gives White good chances. } ( { After looking at c6 we will examine } 3...dxc4 { , } ) ( 3...d4 { , and } ) ( 3...Bg7 { . } ) 
4. e3 {[%cal Bd2d4]} ( { According to Stockfish 15, e3 and } 4.d4 { are best. d4 would actually transpose into a rare version of the Slav Defense, but as e3 naturally falls into our plan, that is our choice. This gives breathing room for the light-squared Bishop and protects the } { c4 pawn. } ) Bg7 {[%csl Gg6]} { Now that g6 has been played and Black's dark-squared Bishop is fianchettoed, we have wandered into the area where Masters play. Black is using the Bishop to compete with White's command of the dark squares. } 
5. Nc3 {[%cal Bc4d5,Bd2d4,Bf1e2]} { We left the confines of our standard plan when c4 was played, as it locks in our light-squared Bishop. It would be convenient if Black would take the pawn so that we could develop with tempo, but that will not happen. We play Nc3 to develop the Knight, and give us the option to fianchetto the dark-squared Bishop, if that happens to be the best continuation. } ( { There are other possibilities from the previous position that are completely legitimate, like } 5.cxd5 { and } ) ( 5.Be2 { is also an option that is appealing, but there are not enough games in the database to properly judge how well it works for us. } )Nf6 { If the Knight is taken 5...Bxc3 then that should not cause problems after 6.bxc3 Nf6 7.Be2 O-O 8.O-O } { Black's best move. } 
6. d4 { At this point we have transposed into a minor variation of the Slav Defense. Minor as that may be, it is a significant position with which we need to be concerned. The remaining variations in this chapter need to be examined, but will probably never be seen.

Win rate in this position: 48% - 47%.

This is the tenth most popular position following White's 6th move, so it will be continued in The Somewhat Likely Continuations. } *

