2. Nf3 {[%csl Be5,Bd4,Bh4]} { This is additional control over the dark squares, as well as protection of the vulnerable h4 square. } ( { This will be our second move every single time, with the exception of From's Gambit. In the past it was not uncommon to see } 2.b3 { played here, the idea being that it ensures that White has an opportunity to fianchetto their queenside Bishop. Without this move it is possible that Black can fianchetto their kingside Bishop and stunt our idea, which is actually the best plan, but seldom played at the club level. There are ways of dealing with that possibility, so the b3 move has fallen out of favor over the years. } ) g6 { This is the best response against our setup, but is seldom played, probably because no club player prepares to play against Bird's Opening. It could be argued that this is a refutation against the opening, as at the Master level the win rate is 23% - 38%. Indeed, at the club level the win rate is only 39% - 55%. However, these are averages, so we should not lose hope, as there is one response to this move that offers White a slightly advantageous win rate. } 
3. c4! {[%mdl 32768]} { I decided to put an exclamation mark on this move because I am not sure that it would be found over the board. At the Master level it would just be 'another move' - and looking at the win rate for White, possibly not one of the more promising ones. More on that in a moment. For the club player the move has a win rate of 48%-47% - the only move with a significant number of games played that keeps White positive in this regard.

When choosing a seldom played move simply because of the win rate, one needs to make sure that it is not a trash move that has had success only because of a dodgy trap, and at first blush it appears that this may be the case.

An initial look at the Masters database shows that c4 gives White the absolute worst win rate amongst the moves played. On second glance, however, the move also offers White the lowest loss rate among its peer moves.

This move has a 62% draw rate, so c4! is not a trash move, but a legitimate attempt to play against the strongest option Black has at their disposal. } Bg7 { Bg7 is the worst of the four responses for Black. } ( { Not covered here is } 3...e6 { , as it is seldom played. However, it causes a number of problems for White as } 4.e3 Bg7 5.Nc3 Ne7 { allow Black a comfortable position. in this case the best final moves in this sequence are either } 6.Rb1 { or } { 6.b4 , the former never having been played and the latter played only once in a Master level game. } ) { No Masters games in this position. } 
4. cxd5 { There is no better choice than to remove a pawn from Black's center, and force the opponent into spending a tempo to retake. } Qxd5 
5. Nc3 { Developing with tempo. } Qd8 {[%cal Gg7c3,Bb2c3]} ( { Best move is to un-develop the Queen. There is no concern with } 5...Bxc3 { since } { 9.bxc3 hands the advantage over to White. } ) 
6. d4 {[%cal Be2e4]} { Either the d- or e-pawn can be pushed - White has a slightly better chance of advancing the center with the d-pawn at this point.

Stockfish 15 evaluation: +0.9

Example games in this position: 1 [/variation/28612448] 2 [/variation/28612450] 3 [/variation/28612455] } *

