1. f4 e6 { The meat of the course was in the 1... d5 chapter. Since 1... e6 is played about two-thirds less this chapter will be shorter. A reasonable question might be, 'Why is e6 the second most popular response to f4?,' to which I have to shrug my shoulders and say that I have no clue. } 
2. Nf3 d6 { Looking at a number of games in the database, Black's idea here is probably to go into a crouch, playing a Hippo Defense ([ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippopotamus_Defence ]) . There is also a Chessable course on the defense that can be found at [ https://www.chessable.com/the-hippopotamus-defence/course/66227/ ] Since they are not familiar with Bird's Opening they pull back and wait to see what develops, which is not a bad idea, but understanding how to take advantage of the situation can make it one.

No Masters games in this position. } 
3. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Since Black is not contesting the center, we will go ahead and take it ourselves. This will be a recurring theme - when Black decides to not contest the center early on, we go ahead and take it. } h6 {[%cal Gf8e7]} ( 3...Be7 { is the best and most popular move for Black from the previous position, and transposes into another variation in this chapter. } ) 
4. d4 { Black is allowing us to take over the center, so we do so without reservations. } a6 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gd6d5,Gg8f6][%csl Gh6]} { a6 mirrors the } { h6 move, but actually has a purpose in restricting White's light-squared Bishop. The other popular move is { 4...g6 , which will be seen in the next variation. Better would have been 4...d5 or 4...Nf6 . } 
5. Bd3 {[%cal Bc2c4]} ( 5.c4 { is a stronger move, but the club player has better success with Bd3, which protects the only unprotected pawn on the fourth rank. } ) b6 { What appears to be another random pawn move is probably part of a Hippo setup. } 
6. O-O { We just work to complete development. Black hopes that we will overextend our pieces and turn the tables on an over-aggressive set of moves. Best at this point is to improve our pieces and be on the lookout for pawn breaks.

Win rate in this position: 68% - 29%.

