1. f4 e5 {[%cal Be2e4]} 
2. fxe5 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This is known as From's Gambit. At first it may appear to be something rather dodgy, like the Englund Gambit, but that is hardly the case. Some Bird's players shy away from it by playing } 2.e4 { and turning the opening into a King's Gambit, but in my mind that opens up a whole new can of worms.

There appears to be a wide discrepancy between the results of Masters and club players. In this position White's winning percentage in the Masters database is 39% - 28%, whereas in the Lichess database it is 46% - 50%.

Stockfish 15 gives this position an evaluation of +0.7. This tells us that Black is close to offering a pawn on their very first move. However, we are not engines and this gambit has an excellent success rate against club players. This is a case where Black has actually prepared against the opening, which is seldom the case, so we need to be on high alert.

This could be played by one with a rating in the 500s, as was seen in Eric Hansen's Speedrun ([ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Azo72KPYVEI ]) . His opponent played a number of moves that could have led to checkmate, but Eric knew what to do. As soon as the one trick was gone the player had nothing. This is why simply understanding the refutation will result in gaining a nice advantage. } ) { We take the pawn and will probably be offered a second pawn. By the way, this is the only move for White, all other moves give Black an advantage as far as the engine is concerned (sorry about that, King's Gambit players) .

Unlike many of the other lines, most of the moves we will learn against From's Gambit will need to be precise and have little wiggle room. That is perhaps the reason that club players do not fare well against this gambit, as they play less precisely than Master level players. Not to worry, however, as the moves we will learn are logical and not difficult to understand. } d6 {[%cal Gb8c6]} ( { There it is. Black may also play } 2...Nc6 { , which is less challenging for us. That variation will be examined following two variations with d6. } ) 
3. exd6 {[%cal Bg1f3]} ( 3.Nf3 { is equally good and will probably transpose back to this variation via } 3...dxe5 4.Nxe5 Bd6 5.Nf3 { Taking the second pawn is fine as long as we are prepared for Black's traps. } ) Bxd6 { This is the idea of From's Gambit, to use the pawn given away as compensation for the advanced development. Black's trap will lie in the fact that White's king is initially exposed to attack, and if one is not careful, checkmate. These are things that can all be dealt with by simply being aware of the potential. From's Gambit is popular amongst players who know the trap and are hoping for a quick win. Knowing how to play against it will just leave Black a pawn down. } 
4. Nf3 ( { The only move, and fortunately, the one we have played on move 2 in every other variation, so it should be completely natural. Any other move can lead to extreme consequences, for instance: } 4.e4 Qh4+ 5.g3 Bxg3+ 6.hxg3 Qxg3 { and it is mate in three more moves. } ) g5 {[%cal Gc8g4]} ( { This is the Lasker variation, one of two equally possible moves for Black - } 4...Bg4 { will be examined next. Quite obviously Black will try to remove the Knight from its post, but with proper play they will just end up over-extending their kingside.

I should mention that while one might think that Lasker used this move on a regular basis to overwhelm his opponents, he actually played it only once, and that was against Henry Bird, probably for its surprise value. } ) 
5. g3 {[%cal Bd2d3,Bd2d4,Rh2h3][%csl Gg5]} ( 5.d4 { and } ) ( 5.d3 { are also good. The g5 pawn will be pushed to } { g4 next. } ) ( 5.h3?? { can end the game, but is the third most common move played. To date, that move has been made almost 1, 500 times, which is why From's Gambit is so popular. However, to my amazement, 15% of the time Black does not capitalize with } 5...Bg3# { , so even a number of those playing the gambit do not know how to play it.

Following g3 White's win rate goes from 42% to 48%. I believe that this is because there are a large number of players with the Black pieces who are expecting h3 to be played, and when that does not happen have no idea what to do next. } ) g4 { Expected. } 
6. Nh4 {[%cal Bf3d4][%csl Bf3]} ( 6.Nd4 { is also a possibility, and can end up with an interesting sequence that Stockfish 15 sees as dead even, but club players only prevail a third of the time: } 6...Bxg3+ 7.hxg3 Qxd4 8.e3 Qd6 9.Rg1 {

Also, Nh4 works as a blockade that prevents Black from advancing their h-pawn beyond h5.

Win rate in this position: 47% - 48%

This is the fourth most popular position following White's 6th move, so it will be continued in The Most Likely Continuations chapter. } ) *

