{ This is a continuation of 2... Nf6 3... e6 with 4... c5 [/variation/21430221]. The position comprises a whopping 1/8 of the total, so it should be understood completely. } 6... Bd7 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { The second most common response by Black in this position is } 6...Be7 { , which will be examined in the next variation. } ) 
7. O-O { The two noticeable things in the previous position are that we have not yet castled and our light-squared Bishop still exists. We remedy that first task at this point.

We could have taken the Knight, but we give Black one more chance to ask the Bishop its intentions. } Be7 { 2...a6 is played half as often, in which case we just take the Knight. Be7 is slightly the better move. } 
8. Bxc6 {[%cal Bf3e5,Ga7a6]} { It is finally time to trade off the Knight. It looks like Black is not going to play a6 and we would like to place our Knight on e5, so removing a defender of that square is timely. } Bxc6 
9. Ne5 {[%cal Bf1f3]} { Tasks at this point are to take advantage of the e5 square that we have developed to occupy, and develop the queenside Knight.

While we have the opportunity, we step into a temporary outpost poking into Black's territory. This also makes the f3 square available in case we wish to do a Rook lift. } O-O ( { Better would have been } 9...Qc7 { , though that is played less than half as often as } { O-O . } ) 
10. Nxc6 {[%cal Bd2d3,Bb1d2,Bd2f3][%csl Ge8]} { It is worth giving up that nice real estate to remove Black's Bishop pair and disrupt the pawn structure. As e8 is available as an escape square for the Bishop, now is a good time to take it before it moves to safety.

After Black retakes, White will look to play d3 and move the Knight to d2, possibly continuing to f3 and taking the place of the Knight that was originally there. Stockfish 15 says that this is an even game.

Win rate in this position: 57% - 37% (81 games)

This will be continued in the Middlegame Play chapter [/variation/23548664]. } *

