{ This is a continuation of 2... Nf6 3... e6 with 4... Be7 and 5... O-O [/variation/21430223]. } 6... c5 {[%mdl 32768]} { This is a well-traveled position, as it is a transposition from the Classical Variation of the Nimzo-Larsen Attack. } 
7. O-O Nc6 
8. Ne5 {[%cal Bd1e1]} ( 8.Qe1 { has a better win percentage, but not only is } { Ne5 a better move, it has a more forcing continuation that leads to a nice position. } ) Nxe5 ( { Black normally takes, which is not a bad move, but better is } 8...Qc7 { , which will be examined in the next continuation. } ) 
9. fxe5 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gf6e5,Bb2e5]} { Taking with the Bishop is not as good, as } { 4.Bxe5 d4 5.Bd3 Nd7 6.Qg4 Nxe5 7.fxe5 f5 8.exf6 Bxf6 and White is in a disadvantageous position. Also, those were the best moves for White - would you have found them? I certainly would not, so my position would certainly be worse.

While taking with the pawn reduces our fianchettoed Bishop's scope, it locks the center for now, and takes the f6 square from Black.

If Black tries to open things up by playing f6 and then taking our e5 pawn, retaking with the Bishop establishes an outpost for the Bishop. } Nd7 
10. c4 {[%cal Bd2d4][%csl Be5,Gd6,Gf6,Be3]} ( { Most Lichess players choose } 10.d4 { , but c4 is a little better choice. This is an even position with chances for both sides. } ) ( { While the e5-pawn does block in the dark-squared Bishop, it does its duty in taking away squares from Black - d6 is not available to Black's Bishop and f6 is not available to the Knight. A plan for Black is to regain that space via } 10.c4 f6 { which can continue } 11.exf6 Nxf6 12.Qe1 d4 13.exd4 cxd4 14.Bf3 Bd6 15.Na3 { resulting in an equal position. } ) ( { It would not be unreasonable to think of playing the typical } 10.d3 { to make room for the undeveloped Knight, but that weakens the e3-pawn and gives Black a small advantage via } 10...Bg5 11.Rf3 d4 12.exd4 cxd4 13.Bxd4 Qc7 { Black will get their pawn back on the next move, and their pieces are better placed after } 14.Rf1 Nxe5 15.Qe1 Rd8 ) { Stockfish 15 evaluation: 0.0

