{ This is a continuation of 2... Be7 with 3... d6 [/variation/21431494]. } 6... Nbd7 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8a6,Gb8c6,Gf6d7,Gf6g4][%csl Gb8]} ( { This is a rather popular position, with thousands of games in the database. The five best moves are } 6...c5 { , } ) ( 6...Na6 { , } ) ( 6...Nc6 { , } ) ( 6...Nfd7 { and } ) ( 6...Ng4 { but we will only look at two of those five, as Black does not play the others. There are three additional moves that we will cover as likely responses. } ) 
7. e5 {[%csl Bh7,Gf6]} { This is the common move that will be seen in each of the five variations. With control of the center we get to start pushing Black around with purpose. Forcing the f6-Knight to move relieves it from the defense of the h7-pawn, which may be useful in a short while. } dxe5 {[%cal Gf6d5]} ( { A fine move - } 7...Nd5 { would have been as good. } ) 
8. fxe5 {[%cal Bf1f8]} { Taking this way opens up the f-file. It not only forces the Knight away, but closes the position a little more, making it a bit more difficult for Black to transfer their pieces while White engages in an attack. } Nd5 { The only move for Black. } 
9. h4 {[%csl Bd3,Gh7,Bf3,Bd1,Bh1]} { This is an important position!

The idea here can win you many games, therefore I will spend a little time with it.

I am not really one for traps, as they too often rely upon misplay by the opponent at the cost of some advantage. Note that the light-squared Bishop is putting pressure on Black's h7 pawn, a Knight is on f3 and the Queen and kingside Rook are in their starting positions. Notice a pattern here? }h6 ( { This is a perfect setup for the Greek gift. If Black is unawares, as was the case in the two games in the database, White can unleash an attack that offers great advantage. The lines for them: [ https://lichess.org/E532qbCX ] } 9...c5 10.Bxh7+ Kh8 11.Nxd5 exd5 12.Ng5 g6 13.Nxf7+ Rxf7 14.Bxg6 Rg7 15.Qh5+ { Eval: +12.0 or, as was the case in the other game, the Knight can be taken first: [ https://lichess.org/gs3FsFI2 ] } ) ( 9...c5 10.Nxd5 exd5 11.Bxh7+ Kh8 12.Ng5 g6 13.Nxf7+ Rxf7 14.Bxg6 Rg7 15.Qh5+ { Eval: +12.0 } ) { The best move for Black. } 
10. Ng5! -- ( { This would certainly be unexpected! If Black unthinkingly takes the Knight: } 10...hxg5 { then } 11.Bh7+ Kh8 12.hxg5 Bxg5 13.Bd3 Bh4+ 14.g3 { and Black is simply lost. If instead of checking Black brings the Bishop back } { 13...Bh6 then they simply lose the Bishop 14.Bxh6 If Black takes with the pawn 14...gxh6 then that sets up a mate in four - can you find it? } { But a cool move without purpose isn't cool, so we could continue: 10...Bb4 11.O-O Nxc3 12.Bh7+ Kh8 13.Qh5 and now Black has to find an unlikely move, like 13...f6 , 13...f5 or 13...Nxe5 to stay less than five pawns down in the evaluation column. } { Just to be clear, after 10...Bb4 11.O-O Black can take the Knight 11...hxg5 but then they need to find the moves to stay alive: 12.Qh5 f5 13.Nxd5 Nxe5! 14.dxe5 Qxd5 15.hxg5 Qd4+ 16.Kh1 Qg4 and Black survives the attack with White holding an advantage. Stockfish 15 evaluation: +2.3

No games in this position.

This will be continued in the Where Did They Go From Here? chapter [/variation/24112215]. } )
