{ This is a continuation of 2... Be7 with 3... d6 [/variation/21431494]. } 6... b6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8a6,Gb8c6,Gf6d7,Gf6g4]} ( { This is a rather popular position, with thousands of games in the database. The five best moves are } 6...c5 { , } ) ( 6...Na6 { , } ) ( 6...Nc6 { , } ) ( 6...Nfd7 { and } ) ( 6...Ng4 { but we will only look at two of those five, as Black does not play the others. There are three additional moves that we will cover as likely responses. } ) 
7. e5 {[%csl Gf6,Bh7]} { This is the common move that will be seen in each of the five variations. With control of the center we get to start pushing Black around with purpose. Forcing the f6-Knight to move relieves it from the defense of the h7-pawn, which may be useful in a short while. } dxe5 {[%cal Gf6d5]} ( { Not as good as } 7...Nd5 { . } ) 
8. fxe5 {[%cal Bf1f8]} { Taking this way opens up the f-file. } Nd5 { Black's only move. } 
9. h4 {[%cal Gd5c3]} f5 ( { White would so much love to see } 9...Nxc3 { played here, as it offers a huge advantage for Black following } 10.Bxh7+ Kh8 11.bxc3 Qe8 12.Be4 { Black cannot take the Bishop, since } { 10...Kxh7 11.Ng5+ and Black needs to play perfectly to stave off forced checkmate 11...Kh6 12.Qd3 g6 13.Nxf7+ and it's basically lights out. } ) 
10. exf6 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gf8f6,Gg7f6,Gd5f6]} { There are four ways to take White's f-pawn, and one is worse than not taking it at all! It would be a good exercise to look at the position to find which piece keeps Black in the game, and which one basically loses on the spot. You may 'pause the video' before I give you the answer.

---

