{ This is really just an add-on chapter that should only be studied once the previous chapters are pretty well digested. Each of the following variations can expect to be encountered 1-1.9% of the time, so it is entirely probable that your time may be better spent working on tactics. However, I did want to be able to claim that the course is somewhat complete for the club player, so I added these continuations.

So look at this chapter as a BONUS chapter, and one that can be ignored without worrying that something critical is passing you by.

That said, I will point out that due to transposition, three of the final positions of these variations actually found their way into the Middlegame Play chapter. I still think that the importance of the variations in this chapter pale in comparison to the others, but it is your choice as to whether or not time should be spent on these variations. } 1. -- *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "The Rather Unlikely Continuations"]
[Black "16"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28756226"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/3p1ppp/p1p1p3/2p5/4PP2/3P1N2/PPP3PP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6"]

{ This is a continuation of 2... c5 [/variation/21431506]. } 6... d5 {[%mdl 32768]} 
7. c4 {[%cal Be1g1,Bd1e2]} { There are a few good options from this position, where White currently holds a small advantage. } ( { Castling } 7.O-O { is a fine move, which may see } 7...Nf6 8.e5 Nd7 9.c4 Be7 { , as has happened in a few dozen games, holding onto that small advantage. Much less often played is the other good move } { 7...c4 , forcing White to break the chain 8.dxc4 Qb6+ 9.Kh1 The check is not threatening, as the King would probably move to h1 at some point anyway. 9...dxe4 10.Ne5 , and while Black's pawns are in the center, defending them will take some energy. } ) ( 7.Qe2 { is an under-appreciated choice, followed by } 7...Be7 8.c4 Nf6 9.Nc3 O-O 10.O-O { White is pushing their center mass forward and looking for the most favorable breaks. } ) { Note that destroying Black's pawn mass with prejudice is integral to the process here. Our intention is to open the center with more active pieces in place. } dxe4 { By far the most common move for Black, and definitely not the best. Simple developing moves would have been better, but Black thinks that they are getting the advantage through the subsequent move. } { 8...d4 is not to be feared, as { 8.e5 or 8.Nbd2 keep everything in check. In an apparent attempt at humor, Stockfish 15 recommends the second best move to be 8.Kd2 , which I may live long enough to have someone explain to me. } 
8. dxe4 Qxd1+ 
9. Kxd1 { If Black thought that removing White's castling rights would be advantageous then they are sorely mistaken. With the Queens off the board, White's King is not only in fine shape, but can move to either side of the board as an attacking piece as the game progresses. } Nf6 
10. Nc3 { Now we simply develop our pieces to good squares. This will not be so easy for Black, as both Bishops are locked in by pawns, which is perhaps why Stockfish 15 evaluates this position as +2.8 and White's win percentage is 68%-25%. 53 games }-- ( { The game could proceed } 10...Be7 { In the 30 database games available, none selected } 11.Kc2 { , as nearly half chose for the King to go to } { e2 . Since Queens are off the board castling is not as important, and in this case c2 was selected because the King may be more useful as an attacking piece on the queenside. 11...Nd7 12.Na4 as both sides eye the vulnerable c5-pawn. 12...f6 looking to break into White's center 13.Be3 e5 14.f5 The pawn could also be taken 14.fxe5 fxe5 , which would open the f-file, but it is not completely clear which side would find that advantageous. }  { Example games in this position: 1 [/variation/28907271] 2 [/variation/28907430] 3 [/variation/28907434] } )
*

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "The Rather Unlikely Continuations"]
[Black "17"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28756227"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "rn1qk2r/pbppbppp/1p2pn2/8/5P2/1P2PN2/PBPPB1PP/RN1QK2R b KQkq - 4 6"]

{ This is a continuation of 2... Nf6 with 3... b6 [/variation/21431492]. } 6... O-O {[%mdl 32768]} 
7. O-O {[%cal Bh1g1][%csl Bh1]} ( { As in the case with one of the e6 variations [/variation/21431489], } 7.Rg1 { would also be completely appropriate. } ) d6 
8. Nc3 {[%cal Bd1e1,Bd2d4]} ( { Getting our last minor piece into the game. } 8.Qe1 { could also be played, but will come next. Stockfish feels that going into a Stonewall with } ) ( 8.d4 { evaluates equal to Nc3 and Qe1, and while the engine may feel that that poses no difficulties, club players with the White pieces tend toward disaster with that move. } ) Nbd7 
9. Qe1 {[%cal Be1g3,Be1h4]} { We move the Queen to a diagonal that will allow it to be active in attacking Black's kingside. } c5 {[%cal Gf6e4]} ( 9...Ne4 { is actually played just a bit more frequently, but it is far from a good move so we look at a response to the much better second most played response. } ) 
10. Qg3 { The Queen is now in attack position. This is a fairly even position where White is ready to move against their opponent's kingside, but Black has well positioned pieces and a strong defense. }-- ( { With only two games in this position we can start with } 10...Rc8 { , the stronger of the two choices. In the database White chose to play } 11.Bd3 { , but a stronger idea is to create a new line and reroute the c3-Knight with } { 11.Nd1 d5 12.Nf2 Black seeing this reroute perhaps thinks to do the same with 12...Ne8 After that pawns are pushed 13.d3 b5 14.c4 and White has the smallest of advantages, meaning that anything can happen. }  { Masters example game in this position: 1 [/variation/29350188]

Example games in this position: 1 [/variation/29343049] 2 [/variation/29343050] } )
*

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "The Rather Unlikely Continuations"]
[Black "18"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28756232"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/pppb1ppp/2n1pn2/1B1p4/5P2/1P2PN2/P1PP2PP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 6"]

{ This is a continuation of 2... Nc6 3... Nf6 with 4... Bd7 and 5... e6 [/variation/21430247]. } 6... a6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
7. Bxc6 {[%cal Bb5e2][%csl Bb5]} { We take when provoked, which is the best move, though in this particular situation dropping the Bishop back to e2 would also be acceptable. } Bxc6 
8. Bb2 {[%cal Bf3e5]} ( { The engine likes } 8.Ne5 { but the two moves are interchangeable, as whichever is the choice, the other will almost certainly be played next. } ) Be7 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gb7b5,Gc6b5,Gb7b6]} ( { This is where Black begins to fall apart. Be7 does protect the Knight so that Black can castle, but places the Bishop in a passive location, turning it essentially into a pawn. This loss of tempo offers White an opportunity to take a small advantage. Better would have been for Black to either begin advancing on the queenside, or play } 8...Bb5 { to make our Rook move to a less favorable square. } ) 
9. Ne5 { A natural attacking square for our Knight. } Bb5 { This move and castling are the two best choices, but now that our Knight is out of the way, we will take this opportunity to lift the Rook. } 
10. Rf3 {[%cal Bd2d3,Bc2c4][%csl Bf1]} ( { White usually plays } 10.d3 { from the previous position, but that is too passive. } ) ( 10.c4 { is an acceptable alternative. } )-- ( { Continuing the line we may see 10...O-O 11.Rh3 - our Rook lift moves into position 11...c5 - preparing to thrust into the center 12.d3 - room for our Knight 12...d4 - now that the d4 square is protected, Black moves to shut down the diagonal. White has a few alternatives, 13.Qf3 and 13.Qe2 are a couple, with 13.c4 being the best to keep the small advantage.

Win rate in this position: 63% - 37% 43 games

Example games in this position: 1 [/variation/29342656] 2 [/variation/29342659] 3 [/variation/29342666] } )
