[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Middlegame Play"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23296770"]

1. -- { Not everything is linear in Chess, but I'm sure that's something you already knew. Even with that knowledge sometimes one can be surprised.

The positions initially offered in The Most Likely Continuations chapter are there because they are the five positions that have the most number of games in the Lichess database, each having at least 3,700 games from which to work. From those five positions we worked through only four moves, which branched out to 13 variations. At the end of these lines one finished with over one thousand games in the database and one finished with none.

The positions initially offered in The Somewhat Likely Continuations chapter started with 10 positions, which expanded to 23. Six of those ended up with more games in the database than seven of the ending positions in the previously mentioned chapter.

Again, this is not linear.

The reason for this is primarily due to the fact that there are a number of transpositions that get us to these positions, and those transpositions come from some rather common openings. While we have selected Bird’s Opening partially as refuge from commonly known theory, we at times stumble into exactly that. The best laid plans of mice and men.

But nobody ever said that this was going to be easy, so now that the actual easy stuff is out of the way, we get to the part where we really need to put our thinking caps on and figure this thing out. Fortunately, it is not an insurmountable task.

I selected the dozen positions from the continuations chapters that are most commonly seen in the database and continued them in this chapter.

As is the case with my other course – The Caro-Kann for Club Players ([ https://www.chessable.com/course/77954 ]) - this Middlegame Play chapter is not one of variations to be memorized. The purpose of this chapter is for one to get accustomed to playing in positions that may arise when playing Bird's Opening. Seeing the position and thinking about what to do will get you considerably further in learning than blindly memorizing moves that will not be seen.

Getting these moves right is not an easy task, so as you go through each variation if you get a soft fail then consider that to be a success (although you still need to find the best move) . I have been generous with the soft fails, manually identifying any move within 0.5 pawns evaluation of the selected move.

For more ideas on the Middlegame you will want to read Ideas for the Middlegame [/variation/24343961]. } *

