{ This is a continuation from 5A1 [/variation/22690746]. } 10... O-O {[%mdl 32768]} { This and the 1B1 and 1B2 variations can be paired together due to their similarities. There are actually seven 'groups' labeled by the first number in their title within these middlegame starting positions, with 1&2 being a set and 7-11 being a set, but each have their own complications. } 
11. Bd2 {[%csl Bg3]} { One may think that the presence of the Queen on g3 indicates that a tactic is in the air, but we do not have anything concrete so far. At this point it is best to move the Bishop off the back rank to connect the Rooks, then see what Black does that may allow a tactic. } b5 {[%cal Gg8h8]} { It is not uncommon for Black to decide to lose a tempo by moving the King to h8. b5 tells us that Black would like to expand on the queenside with their advanced pawns - we want to look for attacking possibilities on the kingside, the direction of our pawn chain. } 
12. Rae1 {[%cal Yf1f8,Ye1e8][%csl Be1]} { This is still a very even position with both sides maintaining chances. The idea is to find ways to improve our pieces. Here we are moving the a-Rook over to strengthen our center pawns. } b4 
13. Nd1 {[%csl Be3,Bf2]} { The best place for the Knight. Placing it on e2 is another possibility, but would block the e-Rook. Nd1 gives us flexibility to move it to e3 or f2 if the situation demands, or it can be used to reinforce the queenside if Black attacks there. } c4 
14. Kh1 {[%cal Gd8b6]} { There is no immediate threat on the queenside so we make a move that will probably be played in most games, which is to take the opportunity to offer a little more security for our King, as the Queen may develop with tempo at a time that is not of our choosing. } a5 { From this point we will look at moves by Black that have been selected by the engine, as there are no games in the database. } 
15. f5 { As Black advances queenside, we advance kingside. Black can try to close things down or allow them to open up. } cxd3 
16. cxd3 { This is an even game with zeroes across the board for numerous subsequent moves.

Stockfish 15 evaluation: 0.0

There are no games in the database in this position. } *

