{ This is a continuation from 5A2 [/variation/22690748].

This position gets broken into two parts, as Black's move 11 diverges. } 10... O-O {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Castling at this point is a mistake, } 10...b5 { would have been much better and kept things even. } ) 
11. f5 { Although our Bishop is still in its starting position, Black's g-pawn looks like a nice target, especially with the King behind it, so we stick our nose in their business. } b5 { There are several moves for Black that would have minimized White's advantage, like } { 10...gxf5 , { 10...Nd7 and 10...Qb6 . 10...e6 follows closely and we will look at that next, but b5 ignores White's position at their own peril. } 
12. Bh6 ( { An aggressive move that intrudes into Black's castled kingside. The engine likes } 12.Ne2 { a little better, as it anticipates Black playing b4, but club players do not, as they fail the few times they have chosen that route. It turns out that we will not care whether or not Black pushed their b-pawn. The engine also likes } ) ( 12.Bg5 { a smidgen better, but that will come next. } ) b4 ( 12...Nh5 { was Black's best move, but this is a tough position for them. Black sees b4 as either a gain of tempo or an intermediate move, but none of that matters. } ) 
13. Ng5 ( 13.Ne2 { is acceptable, and is played in about 3/4 of the over 100 games from the previous position, but with Ng5 we are going in for the kill. } ) Nh5 ( { Now Black plays Nh5. 'Oh No, My Knight!' results in } 13...bxc3 14.fxg6 cxb2 15.Rab1 e5 16.Bxg7 Kxg7 17.Rxf6 { and a lost game for Black. } ) 
14. Bxg7 ( 14.fxg6 { works equally well, and we'll do that next. } ) Kxg7 
15. fxg6 hxg6 
16. Nd5 { Stockfish 15 evaluation: +6.4 }-- ( { This offers White a nice advantage } 16...Bxd5 17.exd5 Qb6 18.Rae1 c4+ 19.d4 Rae8 20.c3 bxc3 21.bxc3 { 16.Ne2 is another possibility, which could continue 16...e5 17.Rxf7+! Kg8 18.Rg7+ Allowing a royal fork is Black's only option. 18...Kxg7 19.Ne6+ } )
