[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Where Did They Go From Here?"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23980627"]

1. -- { 'Try to find a better place, but soon it's all the same' - Peter Cetera

'Well, here's another nice mess you've gotten me into!' - Oliver Hardy

I have a number of books on openings, and all but the pamphlet 'A Modern Approach to Bird's Opening' (1975) look at lines that go to the end of the game. This is fine, and I understand that the idea is to show how an advantage can be turned into a win, but my interest at this point has more to do with learning the initial moves. The rest I can come back to at a later time.

There are a number of variations in this course that are not in the Middlegame Play chapter because there are not enough games in the position to be of interest, and for that reason may have ended at a point where the reader could think that there was more meat on the bone.

If that is the case then you are not the only one thinking that - I have thought it myself. This chapter includes positions that were not continued in the Middlegame Play chapter because there were few, if any, games in the database. However, that does not mean that they have no instructive value, it just means that you will probably not encounter them - as is actually the case with most of the positions in the Middlegame Play chapter.

I marked this chapter Informational because it is not something to be memorized, it is really just additional explanation for those lines where I believe that there is more to be said. This is not a comprehensive chapter where I delve into specifics of moves that will never be seen, but one where some of the aforementioned positions will be continued to see whether or not an advantage could be converted, either in a real game or one that Stockfish played. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
