[Black "3A1"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/24163527"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp1b1pp/2n1p3/3pPn2/3P4/2PB1N2/PP4PP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 1"]

{ This is a continuation from 3A1 [/variation/22880047].

I like this position because the g4 move is not the obvious one I would have in my initial calculations. } 1. g4 { There are games in the database in this position, so we will follow while we can. } { 10...Nh4 is pretty much Black's only choice for the Knight. 11.Nxh4 Bxh4 12.Nd2 as we still need to get developed 12...Rxf1+ 13.Qxf1 Ne7 - not the best choice for Black - 14.Nf3 Ng6 15.Bxg6 hxg6 16.g5 and White has a huge advantage. Better for Black would have been { 13...Bg5 which would have been followed by 14.Nf3 Bxc1 15.Qxc1 and White has an advantage. } { I allowed Stockfish 15 to play the position out and got 11.Nxh4 Rxf1+ 12.Qxf1 Bxh4 13.Nd2 Bg5 14.Nf3 Bxc1 15.Qxc1 Bd7 16.Ng5 g6 17.Qf4 Qf8 18.Rf1 Qxf4 19.Rxf4 Re8 20.Rf6 Re7 21.h4 Nd8 22.h5 h6 23.Nh3 gxh5 24.gxh5 Rg7+ 25.Bg6 Ba4 26.Kf2 I found it instructive to see how White is able to force Black to spend time and energy in defense of their weak e-pawn. I stopped at move 26 where there is still piece equality, but it is clear that White has a winning advantage, and Stockfish 15 evaluates the position at +5.0. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Where Did They Go From Here?"]
[Black "7A"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/24112215"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pppnbpp1/4p2p/3nP3/3P3P/2NB1N2/PPP3P1/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0 1"]

{ I think of the following five variations as the '7' series because they each start with that number. Each begins with a position that may possibly involve the Greek Gift, so while the five positions combined add up to only eight games in the database, that does not means they are not instructive. } 1. Ng5 {[%cal Bd3h7,Bd1h5,Bc1h6,Bh1h8][%csl Bh4,Bg5,Bd3,Bd1]} { This is a continuation from 7A [/variation/22967824].

We see here the possibility for the Greek Gift, a light-squared Bishop pointed at h7, a Knight on g5 (or can be placed there) , and a Queen that can be transported to the h-file. In this position we have a pawn on h4 and in subsequent positions we will move a pawn there to support a Knight on g4, as Black has a battery on the d8-h4 diagonal (when this is not the case then the pawn may not be necessary) . There are no games in the database, so we will be selecting Black's moves from Stockfish 14.

As a starting point we can see that the Knight on d7 is basically in the way, and the light-squared Bishop is worthless, so that is a great starting point. } { As we read in the stem variation, the immediate thought of } { 10...hxg5 does not work because of 11.Bh7+ Kh8 12.hxg5 Bxg5 13.Bd3+ Bh4+ 14.g3 and Black is simply lost. } { 10...Bxg5 is not much better, as 11.hxg5 Nb4 12.Ne4 Nxd3+ 13.Qxd3 and since 13...Nxe5 is Black's best move one can see that for all practical purposes the game is over. }{ Black's best move is 10...Bb4 , so we castle out of the way 11.O-O The expected and best move 11...Nxc3 is followed by an incursion into Black's castled position with 12.Bh7 Kh8 For the club player such as myself, Bh7 is not an easy move to find, which is unfortunate because all other moves either equalize or give Black an advantage. } { My question, as must be the case for most of those going through the course, is concerned with how one would see this sequence of events in the first place. The easy answer has to do with calculation and visualization, but if we return to the beginning of this variation we can get a clue.

The seed of figuring this out from the start is the position of our pieces. For one, I am hoping that the general placement of the pieces will alert one to the possibility of the Greek Gift. In this case we are not actually taking a pawn on h7, but the idea is the same.

Also, look at the starting position and evaluate the activity of the pieces on each side. Black, for the most part, is stuck in a cocoon with their pieces stumbling over one another. One Knight is active and the Bishop has few opportunities, all other pieces are just sitting around. On the other hand both of White's Bishops have nice paths on strong diagonals, with the Queen's Rook being the only piece that is not participating.

This scenario means that tactics may be in the air. It means that since you have numerous possibilities and your opponent has few, this is a situation where it is prudent to spend some time to try to work through them. Open positions favor the attacker, so look at even those possibilities where material might be sacrificed to open things up for the attacking pieces.

In the end yes, it does come down to calculation and visualization, there is no way around it, but when positions like this arise then there should be a little person on your shoulder telling you to slow down and consider moves that from the onset may make no sense, as they could result in something quite different. } *

