[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/24134232"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pp2bppp/4p3/3nP3/3p3P/2NB1N2/PPP3P1/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0 1"]

{ These next two positions involve the Greek Gift. } 1. Bxh7+ { This is a continuation from 7C [/variation/23210175].

There are games in the database where the King takes the Bishop, as well as the better decision to move the King to h8. We will look at the latter first. } { This is an instance where Black needs to accept that they are a pawn down with } { 10...Kh8 The database only includes the suboptimal continuation Ng5, which is okay, but there is no need to allow Black to endanger our pawn structure by taking the c3 Knight, so we take theirs first. 11.Nxd5 Qxd5 This is a situation where we accept the fact that there is simply not enough firepower for a full-on attack of the King, so we play the quiet 12.Bd3 Attempting to continue with { 12.Ng5 runs into 12...Qxg2 13.Be4 Qg3+ 14.Kf1 g6 and the advantage is minimal. } { There are some situations when in this general position it makes sense to take the Bishop, but not here. This exposes the King and the true power of the Greek Gift is shown with 10...Kxh7 11.Ng5+ Kh6 , which is Black's only move to hold off forced mate. Nonetheless, after 12.Nxf7+ the game is over. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Where Did They Go From Here?"]
[Black "7D"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/24161519"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp1bppp/2n1p3/4P3/3P3P/2nB1N2/PPP3P1/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0 1"]

{ This is a continuation of 7D [/variation/22967831].

This position is found four times in the database, two times the Knight on c3 was taken and the other two times the Greek Gift was employed. In one of those latter two games White lost because they blundered the tactic, so we will look at that failure also. It goes without saying that the Greek Gift does not ensure a win - only Checkmate does that. } 1. Bxh7+ { As with the previous variation, it is best for Black to not take the Bishop. Doing so } { 10...Kxh7 leads to 11.Ng5+ Black has only one move that does not result in forced mate, 11...Kh6 , and following 12.Nxe6+ taking the Queen is not even the best move. We will stop here, as it will be instructive for you to figure out what the better move(s) are. } { 10...Kh8 There is no sense leaving the Queen in jeopardy and not taking the Knight, so 11.bxc3 and Black is down 5+ pawns evaluation. The best reply is Bd7 but the database player exacerbated their situation with 11...f5 . One bad move nullifies 40 good ones. Can you find the best move in this position? In the game 12.Ng5 was played, followed by 12...Qe8 and 13.h5 and Black has a slight advantage. Best was 12.Bg6! then after 12...f4 we have either 13.Bxf4 or 13.Ng5 and the game is over. } *

