{ This is a continuation from 11A1 [/variation/29969152].

It may seem that we left this position without clear resolution and that is probably the case, so we will follow it for a while. As there are no games in the database we will use Stockfish to guide the decisions. } 1. Qg4 -- ( 1...Kh8 { is really Black's only move here. Something else that might look good, such as } ) ( 1...Ng6 { runs into } 2.Nf6+ gxf6 3.Bxg6 { and taking the pawn } 3...fxg6 { results in } 4.Qxg6+ { @@StartFEN@@r1bqr2k/ppp1nppN/1bn1p2p/3pP3/3P1PQ1/2PB4/PP4PP/RNB1K2R w KQ - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2.Qh5 with the f7-pawn being a possible target 2...Bxd4 Black's plan is to remove the defender of our embedded Knight 3.Ng5 If we take the Bishop 3.cxd4 then that gives Black some counterplay 3...Nb4 4.Qh3 c5 5.Nc3 Nxd3+ 6.Qxd3 cxd4 Repositioning the Knight keeps the piece available for attack. } { @@StartFEN@@r1bqr2k/ppp1npp1/2n1p2p/3pP1NQ/3b1P2/2PB4/PP4PP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ 3...Rf8 Ensuring against a royal fork is paramount 4.Nxf7+ Rxf7 5.Qxf7 Gaining the exchange 5...Bc5 6.Nd2 It is time to get more pieces into the attack. This position is not necessarily winning, but Stockfish 15 sees it as +3.5. } )
*

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
