10. d3 {[%cal Bb1d2]} { We open a slot for the Knight to develop, as we would prefer to keep the a1-h8 diagonal available to our dark-squared Bishop. This is a quieter move than the alternative. } ( 10.c4 { is the alternative. After } 10...dxc4 { we do not take back with } 11.Bxc4 { because of } 11...b5 { so } { 11.bxc4 Of the two games in the database, 11...Rd8 is the stronger of the two, x-raying our Queen. In that game 12.Bf3 Qd7 13.Bc3 Rb8 14.Na3 a6 kept things equal, but 15.Nc2 was an error and the beginning of White's decline and eventual demise. Better would have been 12.d3 to give the Knight a better place to develop. With 12...Qd7 13.a4 b6 14.Nd2 Bb7 15.Qe1 we end up in a similar position. } ) b6 {[%cal Bc8b7][%csl Bc5]} { Offering a place for Black's light-squared Bishop to go, as well as adding a little more protection to the c-pawn. } ( 10...b5 { also works well for Black, as White will probably attack kingside and Black will probably go for a queenside attack. in that case } 11.a4 { would be an appropriate response. } ) 
11. Qe1 {[%cal Be1h4]} ( { We move the Queen so that it can utilize a more useful diagonal. } 11.Nd2 { is an equal possibility, so it does not really matter which move goes first. } ) Bb7 { The obvious placement for Black's light-squared Bishop. } 
12. Nd2 { Getting the Knight into the game. } Rad8 { Black places the Rook on a more central location. } ( { The engine offers } 12...b5 { as a possibility, but psychologically how many of us would consider moving a pawn twice this way. } ) ( 12...a6 { may be a bit more palatable. } ) 
13. Qg3 { There may appear to be an attack here, but this is really more along the lines of improving pieces. Both sides are shuffling their pieces, trying to find more active locations for them. Black has things well defended and the position is equal. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Warmup Puzzles"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23730253"]

{ It is hard to know what this chapter should be called. When we think of a 'Puzzle' what comes to mind is a position where a tactic leads to checkmate or major piece advantage. That is not really the idea here.

The purpose of this chapter is to present a couple dozen positions that we have seen throughout the course and simply look for the right move. Yes, this has already been done, so in theory you should be able to rip through the series using the knowledge you have already gained. However, taking the position out of the context of the previous moves forces one out of an automatic learned response.

One of my personal issues is that as awesome as the MoveTrainer is, the downside is that I sometimes learn through move order, meaning that I have learned a move in response to the previous move. When I come across an exception, not thinkingly I make the wrong move. I need to slow down, just as I should in a game, and take time to look at the position, then think about it one more time before responding.

Some of these are easy, others involve an exception you hopefully remember, so as in a game, think before making your choice.

There are no soft fails for these puzzles, as there was no soft fail when the position was initially presented. We give and take a couple of tenths of a pawn evaluation on a regular basis, but if you miss one of these then you have given away at least half a pawn.

This chapter is best utilized by working through the series before playing a game, as it can be seen as a quick review of what may come to be. I have scrambled the order of these puzzles so that they are not presented in the order in which they were originally seen. If someday Chessable's software allows for random order presentation then that should be selected.

Good luck! } 1. -- *

