1. -- { This is a chapter that I am hoping to continually expand. The idea came to me from a Lichess study I started a while back called Correcting My Bonehead Moves. That was a collection of positions where I had not found the best move and lost an advantage or which led to a much more difficult game. I decided to start listing some of them so that I could turn off the engine, look at the position, and try to figure out what I should have done. Some were tactical misses, others just oversights of things I should have seen. To wit, this is an extension of that idea that can include any interesting position that stems from Bird's Opening where a sharp move must be found.

There are times when reviewing a game that I encounter a position where White has only one or two best moves, and all others drop the evaluation bar at least a pawn. I would love to claim that I have found all of these moves, but that just has not been the case. Some I have seen while playing, others I simply missed.

This chapter is a collection of those positions, where the situation happened within the first 20 or so moves. There are either one or two moves that must be played or the evaluation will drop at least a pawn. The idea here is to find the best move, and if there is a soft fail then the other move needs to be found. This is a critical point in the game, whether or not that was recognized at the time. The move will not be the simple recapture of a Rook or something obvious like that, but will involve something a bit more obtuse.

These are the sorts of puzzles that I feel are helpful to me. I enjoy working on the puzzles that we all employ to build our tactical skills, but those are situations where we know for a fact that some line leads to checkmate or a real advantage. During a game we do not have this knowledge, and anyway, the vast majority of our moves involve simply improving our pieces or successfully attacking/defending a position.

Each puzzle here comes from an actual game where Bird's Opening was played, and by move 20 or 25 (so that at least some structure of the opening still exists) there was a position where only one or two moves were at least a pawn evaluation over all others. Perhaps a tactic is involved, perhaps the move protects a piece that will come under attack, who knows? The only thing for certain is that this is an important point in the game.

I should note that some of these are easy and some more difficult. There may also be some that appear to be easy but that ease may be deceptive, so take a little time before committing to an answer.

But this is where you come into the picture. There is no need for me to be the only one to fill up this chapter. When you play Bird's Opening I am sure that you will see these same situations when you analyze your own game. If you come across a position that meets the above mentioned criteria then let me know and I will add it to the chapter. This can be a game played by you, or even just a game that you were analyzing that was played by someone else. It does not have to involve an actual missed opportunity, it can just be any situation where there is only one or two non-obvious choices required. Either you can annotate it or I can give it a try. You can either get full credit for it or just remain anonymous.

If you would like to participate then send me an email via George.Smyth@gmail.com and use the subject 'Puzzle for Bird's Opening' so that I recognize it (if you don't hear back from me within a day or two then something went wrong and I didn't get it) . Send me the FEN and analysis (if you wish) , and if I think that it is instructive then I will add it to the course. Hey, I'm not the only one who should have fun around here.

I think that it will be enjoyable to build this chapter in a way that gives everyone a chance to continue learning and practicing what to do after the opening has run its course, and with your participation we can all learn together. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Community Puzzles"]
[Black "1"]
