1. g4 ( { The only other move that does not lead to equality from the previous position is } 1.b4 { which Stockfish 15 shows to offer about a one pawn advantage. } )-- ( { g4 doubles that advantage. Stockfish initially feels that the best response is to retreat the Bishop with 1...Bh7 , which allows White to continue the attack with 2.g5 hxg5 3.fxg5 Ne4 4.Bd3 Bg6 5.b4 and White is very comfortable. }{ A deeper dive into Stockfish shows 1...Be4+ to be a bit better. Regardless, White grabs a nice advantage with 2.Nxe4 Nxe4 3.Nd7 Qa7 4.Nxf8 } )
