1. Nbd2 -- ( { While almost any move retains the advantage, Nbd2 pushes the eval bar above the 5 mark. The game could continue } 1...Bg7 2.Ne4 O-O 3.g4 f5 { and } 4.Nd6 { just sticks a finger in Black's eye. } { 1...Nf5 is not much better for Black, as 2.g4 may look like a blunder after 2...Ne3 but we sack the exchange with 3.Qe1 Nxf1 4.Ne4 Black gets what they can with the Knight 4...Nxh2 5.Kxh2 Bf8 but White pushes on with 6.Nf6+ Kd8 7.Qh4 and Black's pieces are stuck on the queenside while White attacks the kingside. } { Black cannot take the pawn with 1...Bxf4 because of the continuation 2.Ne4 Bxc1 3.Qxc1 Nf5 4.Nf6+ Kd8 5.Bxf5 exf5 6.Qh6 and with Qg7 on the way it is time for Black to resign. } )
