1. -- { Congratulations for making it through the course (unless you just came here to see what a Postface was - and for that too, Congratulations!) !

Throughout the course of writing the course (of course!) I have made some notes that I wanted to be included somewhere. As I have exhausted what I feel to be a compromise of reasonable explanation and brevity, I decided to add this final chapter as a repository for those things that just did not fit into a more proper location. So this miscellany can be read, ignored, or relegated to those times when you are waiting in line at the grocery store and just want something to read.

That said, I hope that there is reasonable substance here, so my intention is to remain on point and offer something constructive. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Postface"]
[Black "Ideas for the Middlegame"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/24343961"]

{ It is certain that during game play either of two things will happen:

1.) You will reach the end of the prep that has been offered in the course, or more probably

2.) Either you or your opponent will leave the lines you have studied.

In either of these cases it will then be time to 'just play Chess.' As you enter the point of searching for candidate moves there are a number of good places you can begin, as they are iconic to the opening.

Below I have listed a number of jumping off points that may or may not be relevant to the position at hand. These are in the order I thought of the moves, so do not weigh one over another through that context.

b3 If you have a string of pawns along the c3-e5 diagonal then you will almost certainly not be fianchettoing your dark-squared Bishop. However, if this is not the case then you may consider this move to do exactly that, as long as the Bishop is not relegated to protecting the f4-pawn.

Bc1 It is not every day that we consider un-developing a piece in the normal context of things, but if Black has blocked the c3-e5 diagonal then rerouting the dark-squared fianchettoed Bishop for it to reside on the c1-h6 diagonal might be the right course of action.

Rab1 This move is seen in a variety of middlegames where White decides to open a second front on the queenside. If there is a fianchettoed Bishop on b2 then it can support it if Black has similarly done so with their dark-squared Bishop.

Kh1 The absence of a pawn on f2 means that the castled King can be vulnerable along the g1-a7 diagonal. This is a prophylactic move that ensures against a double attack that may happen later in the game.

a4 Not normally seen early on, this can act as a deterrent against a sudden queenside attack by Black.

h3 If a Bishop is pinning our Knight on f3 then this is the beginning of removing it. The pin is seldom an issue, as we normally slide the Queen to e1, but can be the beginning of a kingside attack with tempo if Black has fianchettoed their dark-squared Bishop..

h4 This might be useful in a situation where a Greek Gift may be possible, supporting a Knight on g5, with the pawn's absence if the Knight is taken making the h-file available for the Rook.

Bxc6/Ba4/B? The light-squared Bishop usually gets traded for Black's c6 Knight, but when a6 is not played White has a choice of what to do with it. If Black's Knight is still on c6 and taking it can double Black's pawns then it may be helpful to make the trade. If there is no longer a pin then moving the Bishop away from the somewhat vulnerable spot and placing it on a better situated square may be prudent. As is the case with everything listed here, this needs to be taken in the context of the position.

Rf2/Rf3 Without a pawn on f3 and a pawn still on g2, a Rook lift may be made in preparation for storming the kingside. Another consideration may be to double the Rooks on the f-file to do the same.

Pawn breaks As middlegame play ensues it is important to consider all pawn breaks by both sides - which ones might happen, and how would they benefit either side. Are there moves that can be made in preparation for a pawn break? Should the position be opened up or shut down? So many questions, and alas, so little time.

Hopefully this list can be used as a starting point for figuring out how to get from where you are to where you want to be. You may also wish to add to this list as you play the opening, as your style and results may lead to you list items that are more relevant to positions you actually end up seeing. } 1. -- *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Postface"]
[Black "The Greek Gift"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23929243"]

{ In The Somewhat Likely Continuations [/course/132444/6] chapter the variations that begin with the number “7” include the possibility for what is referred to as The Greek Gift. I was going to offer a lengthy explanation here but it is safe to assume that this is something that is already understood. If that is not the case then a nice presentation can be found at [ https://www.chess.com/terms/greek-gift-chess ].

It is important to understand the concept of the sacrifice because the natural possibility for this is not uncommon. I refer to this as “natural” because we are not compromising our position or playing “Hope Chess” with the wish that this will happen, but the possibility may occur during the course of playing the moves that are best for us.

As the Greek Gift is a natural possibility, it is as important to understand the sacrifice as it is to learn any other tactic. It can win a game, it can grant White an advantage, and its misuse can lose the game for White, so it makes sense to spend time with it. Hopefully, some day someone will offer a Chessable course that focuses on it.

It is beyond the scope of this course to work through the intricacies of the Classic Bishop Sacrifice, but a couple of Chess.com articles can be found at [ https://bit.ly/ClassicBishopSacrifice1 ] and [ https://bit.ly/ClassicBishopSacrifice2 ].

I have also collected a number of example games that can be found in a Lichess study at [ https://bit.ly/GreekGiftExamples ], which is instructive, as the group shows the variety of ways the tactic has been successfully, and unsuccessfully, employed.

When you have a full grasp of the idea, I recommend returning to the “7” series in The Somewhat Likely Continuations chapter. 7A is an interesting example, 7B is a possibility that does not really work, but leads to an advantage, 7C and 7D are actual attempts, and 7E is probably a successful defense against it.

My suggestion is to work through these with an engine; then try playing against the engine to test your knowledge. This sacrifice can be a deadly trap that is natural, but will also test your calculation and visualization skills.

And speaking of tests, I came across [ https://bit.ly/GrGTest ] which is a nice test of your ability to successfully identify whether or not your position should employ the tactic. } 1. -- *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Postface"]
[Black "The Dutch Defense"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23929803"]

1. -- { So why are we talking about the Dutch Defense in a course about Bird’s Opening? In case you have not noticed, The Bird is pretty much the Dutch with colors reversed and an added tempo. This begs the question as to why the former is considered to be substandard by some who also feel that the latter is completely fine – a question I will not get into, but there it is.

But the point I wanted to make is that if one is learning openings and Bird’s Opening is one of those that is firmly within one’s grasp. It only makes sense to consider the Dutch Defense as an alternative against 1.d4. } ( { The Classical Dutch moves are pretty much the same: } 1.d4 f5 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 e6 4.Bg5 Bb4 { . Most Lichess players employ the more passive Be7, but they have a better win percentage with Bb4. At the Master level they also do things backwards, where Bb4 is more popular but they have better success with the move Be7 - go figure. } ) { If it sounds like the beginnings of a course then you are right. If you think that I am going to write it then you are wrong – this is a course that you can write yourself. I can suggest reviewing How Moves Were Decided [/variation/22857736] and just go from there.

If you really do not want to go through the work then I see that Simon Williams’s Short & Sweet: Classical Dutch is available for free ([ https://www.chessable.com/short-sweet-classical-dutch/course/26772/ ]) , so that could be a starting point from someone who is an expert in the system.

The bottom line is that in learning Bird’s Opening you are also learning the Dutch Defense and can use the same ideas, so it may be fun to give it a try. } *

[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Postface"]
[Black "Transpositions"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23932019"]

1. b3 { There are transpositions in most openings and such is also the case with Bird’s Opening. I have seen transpositions from the French Defense, the Nimzowitsch Defense, the Scandinavian Defense, and numerous others. Perhaps the most common is the Nimzo-Larsen Attack.

I have played 1.b3 for a very long time and have seen that, like Bird's Opening, club players with the black pieces just have no idea what to do. }-- ( { A typical sequence is } 1...d5 2.Bb2 c5 3.f4 e6 4.e3 Nf6 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Bb5 { which brings us to the most common position we will see following the first six moves in the Bird. It is an equal position where both sides have plenty of chances, though the win percentage for all likely moves by Black at this point are quite positive for White. } { Another possible sequence to get us to the same position is 1...c5 2.Bb2 Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 4.f4 e6 5.Nf3 d5 6.Bb5 where Black considers an English style of doing things. } { One could see an Indian style of development with 1...Nf6 2.Bb2 e6 3.e3 d5 4.f4 c5 5.Bb5+ Nc6 6.Nf3 } { Another possibility with a different move order in the first four moves is 1...e6 2.Bb2 c5 3.e3 d5 4.f4 Nf6 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Bb5 } ) { Perhaps it is my familiarity with the Nimzo-Larsen Attack that makes me less trepidatious than others when it comes to learning Bird's Opening. Both are not commonly played (they are about the same in popularity in the database and have the same very general strategy of dominating the b2-h8 diagonal.

The two openings are alike in that the opponent is quickly placed into a position where they need to 'just play Chess' instead of relying on memorized moves, so you may wish to consider looking into 1.b3 somewhere along the line, as you will probably get familiar positions. } )
*

