[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28569492"]

1. -- { This chapter is a collection of games that have been played that are continuations of variations within the course. The intention is to offer a quick and easy means of seeing examples of what might happen from the point where we leave the line.

That being the case, there are no annotations. To follow the games I would recommend that the pgn be tossed into a program that will analyze the position and assist in understanding the moves.

As these are actual games by Lichess players in the 1600-2200 range in Rapid, Classical, and Correspondence time controls, there will be mistakes, blunders, brilliancies, expected moves, and a panoply of ideas club players have when moving wooden pieces around a board.

One of my beta testers noted that it was discouraging to see so many Bird openings end in defeat, and he has a point. Not all positive positions lead to victory, and we are prone to blunders and mistakes. Such is the Chess life.

To be clear, it is the luck of the draw as to which games were selected in these chapters - I usually just grabbed the three most recent games in the Lichess database (some games I decided not to include if they ended very quickly due to a massive blunder, thus were not instructive) . I believe that there may be an instance where all three games were losses.

I realize that many courses only show successful games. We would all like to think that learning the opening well will lead to victory, but it is only the start of the journey. Best case scenario is that learning these moves will give you an extra couple of steps in the race to the finish line, you need to do the rest yourself.

The important thing here is for you to farm these games for ideas. By seeing what went right as well as what went wrong, you can get an idea as to what to embrace and what to avoid. As I have told my children, one can learn from a bad example as well as a good example. } *

