[Event "The Classical Bird for Club Players"]
[White "Other Game Examples"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.08.15"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28613828"]

1. -- { Well done, you, for looking at an Introduction that by all logical means should be redundant. I will just make note here that I highly recommend looking through some of these games, as many can be quite instructive.

One of the things that should be obvious, but can get lost in the shuffle of learning lines, is that these games were not selected because they follow the course recommended moves, though that is certainly possible, but were done by the position at the point where we ended examination of the variation. For example, the 2... Be7 with 3... d6 and 4... Nd7 examples all started with 1.e4, then by move 6 found themselves in a position that is covered within this course.

I love Chessable's MoveTrainer, as a matter of fact, it is what interested me in the website in the first place. But we use the MoveTrainer in a way that (and perhaps I am just speaking for myself) we get locked into the exact sequence of moves that need to be learned, as opposed to evaluating the position. I get caught in that situation on a regular basis, where I think that I am out of theory because the line is not being followed, only to realize later on that the game has transposed itself back into a known line.

So looking at some of these games can highlight the fact that not only can we arrive at a specific position in a number of ways, but oftentimes they do not even start with Bird's Opening. Of course, once you play a certain number of moves and need to find how best to continue, it no longer matters how you got these, you need to deal with the position at hand.

Enjoy. } *

